'Bicol Express'' train].</ref>\n|-\n|1500 (1,200&nbsp;hp BBB locomotive)\n|\n|[[Alstom|Alsthom]]\n|1966-1967\n|6\n|Diesel-electric [[boxcab]]<br>(Converted from [[Electric locomotive|electric]])\n|{{Convert|90|km/h|mph|abbr=on}}\n|Decommissioned in 1987<ref>[https://www.flickr.com/photos/fairlane/3286676399/in/photostream/ MRR/PNR Alsthom Promotional Poster (1966) \u2013 Flickr].</ref><ref>[https://www.flickr.com/photos/79691913@N05/10536055134/in/pool-1395212@N21/ ''Locomotives for PNR'' From the Sunday Chronicle - Nov. 20, 1966]</ref>\n|-\n|[[GE UM12C|2000]]\n|\n|GE Transportation\n|1956\n|20\n|Diesel-electric<br>[[Road switcher]]\n|{{Convert|60|km/h|mph|abbr=on}}\n|Decommissioned in 1997<ref name=\"12c\">[http://thedieselshop.us/GE_UM12C.HTML ''GE UM12C Roster''.] The Diesel Shop.</ref><ref name=\"b\">{{cite web |url= http://www.locopage.net/ge-expt-lst.doc|title=GE Export|author=Phil's Loco Page|date=July 4, 2015}}</ref><ref>[https://www.flickr.com/photos/fairlane/5542113579/ PNR UM12C Image (1961) \u2013 Flickr].</ref><ref name=\"mrr\"/>\n|-\n|[[PNR 2500 class|2500]]\n|[[File:PNR Kiha 52 (ex-JR) train (Anonas Street, Santa Mesa, Manila)(2017-07-12) 2.jpg|200px]]\n|GE Transportation\n|1965-79\n|43\n|Diesel-electric switcher\n|{{Convert|103|km/h|mph|abbr=on}}\n|2 units in service<ref name=\"is\" /><ref name=\"12c\" />\n|-\n|3000 (50-ton)\n|\n|GE Transportation\n|1955\n|10\n|Diesel [[switcher]]\n|{{Convert|51|km/h|mph|abbr=on}}\n|Decommissioned\n|-\n|3000 (U6B)\n|\n|GE Transportation\n|1960\n|10\n|Diesel-electric\n|{{Convert|103|km/h|mph|abbr=on}}\n|Rebuilt and renumbered as \"5000 Class\" in 1992<ref name=\"12c\" />\n|-\n|5000\n|\n|GE Transportation\n|1992 (rebuilt from 3000 Class)\n|10\n|Diesel-electric\n|{{Convert|103|km/h|mph|abbr=on}}\n|Not in active service since 2017<ref name=\"is\">[http://www.internationalsteam.co.uk/trains/philippines01.htm ''Today's Railways and Preserved Steam in the Philippines'']. International Steam. Retrieved December 18, 2019.</ref><ref name=\"12c\" /><ref>[https://www.flickr.com/photos/46273205@N02/5432493069/in/pool-1395212@N21/ DEL 5009 in 2010]</ref><ref>[https://www.flickr.com/photos/46273205@N02/26592807702/in/pool-1395212@N21/ DEL 5001 in 2016]</ref>\n|-\n|[[GE 44-ton switcher|8500]]\n|\n|GE Transportation\n|1944\n|2\n|Diesel-electric\n|\n|Decommissioned<ref>{{Cite web|title=8591 Caloocan|url=https://vignette.wikia.nocookie.net/philippinetrains/images/0/0a/8591_caloocan.png/revision/latest?cb=20170323005354&path-prefix=tl|website=Philippine Trains Wikia|access-date=March 16, 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[GE U20C|CC203]]\n|\n|[[Industri Kereta Api|PT INKA<br>GE Lokindo]]\n|1998\n|1\n|Diesel-electric\n|{{Convert|120|km/h|mph|abbr=on}}\n|Operated with ICTSI<br>Decommissioned, exported to Australia<ref name=\"12c\" />\n|-\n|CC300 ([[:id:Lokomotif CC300|id]])\n|\n|[[Industri Kereta Api|PT INKA]]\n|2020\n|3\n|[[Diesel locomotive|Diesel-hydraulic]]\n|{{Convert|120|km/h|mph|abbr=on}}\n|Undergoing tests<ref name=\"Inquirer-7Trains\">{{Cite web|url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/995374/pnr-buys-seven-more-trains-worth-p2-37-b-from-indonesia|title=PNR buys seven more trains worth P2.37-B from Indonesia|first=Dexter|last=Cabalza|website=newsinfo.inquirer.net}}</ref>\n|-\n|}\n\n===Coaches===\nPNR trains were traditionally consisted of locomotive-hauled coaches with some being refurbished from commuter rail to intercity use to accommodate the ''Bicol Express''. However, since the early 2010s, the government has put several diesel multiple units into service which were either second-hand Japanese trainsets or the Hyundai Rotem EMU that was new at the time. Currently, the only locomotive-hauled railcar type in service are the [[203 series]]-derived coaches which were EMUs stripped of motive power components which they have used during their Japanese service. By 2020, it is expected that a batch of 15 coaches will arrive from Indonesia.<ref name=\"Inquirer-7Trains\" />\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|+ Coaches\n! Class  \n! Image\n! Manufacturer\n! Year Built\n! Units Built\n! Status\n|-\n| 7A-100\n|\n| [[Nippon Sharyo]], [[Kinki Sharyo]], [[Teikoku Sharyo]], Mecano\n| 1949-1978\n| \u2014\n| Decommissioned before 1999.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.flickr.com/photos/fairlane/4831029248/|title=1973 Mayon Express Ltd|date=July 26, 2010|via=Flickr}}</ref>\n|-\n| CMC 200\n|\n| \n| 1974\n| \u2014\n| 1 unit for its rerailment crew active as of 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=_CVnadWcsWo|title=PNR 917 passing Gumaca, Quezon|date=September 21, 2019|via=Youtube}}</ref>\n|-\n| 7A-2000<br><small>([[:ja:\u56fd\u924412\u7cfb\u5ba2\u8eca|12 series passenger coach]], ex-[[Japanese National Railways]])</small>\n| [[File:PNR Tayuman 2009 MC.jpg|200px]]\n| Niigata Engineering<br>[[Subaru Corporation#History|Fuji Heavy Industries]]<br>[[Nippon Sharyo]]\n| 1969-1978<br>(acquired 1999, 2001)\n| 26\n| Decommissioned\n|-\n| 7A-2000<br><small>([[:ja:\u56fd\u924414\u7cfb\u5ba2\u8eca|14 series passenger coach]], ex-[[Japanese National Railways]])</small>\n| \n| Niigata Engineering<br>[[Subaru Corporation#History|Fuji Heavy Industries]]\n| 1972, 1974<br>(acquired 1999)\n| 5\n| Decommissioned\n|-\n| NR-00<br><small>(12 series [[:ja:\u56fd\u924412\u7cfb\u5ba2\u8eca|ja]])</small>\n| [[File:Old PNR Train.JPG|200px]]\n| Niigata Engineering<br>[[Subaru Corporation#History|Fuji Heavy Industries]]<br>[[Nippon Sharyo]]\n| 1969-1978<br>(acquired 2002)\n| 10\n| Decommissioned\n|-\n| 14 series sleeper\n| [[File:PNR Bicol Express 14-series coaches at Tutuban Yard.jpg|200px]]\n| Kawasaki Heavy Industries<br>Fuji Heavy Industries<br>''Others''\n| 1966-1979 (acquired 2011)\n| 10\n| On storage<ref name=\"sankei\">{{cite web|url=http://sankei.jp.msn.com/life/news/111126/trd11112612010008-n1.htm|date=November 26, 2011|work=Sankei News|publisher=The Sankei Shimbun & Sankei Digital|location=Japan|language=Japanese|script-title=ja:\u65e5\u672c\u306e\u4e2d\u53e4\u96fb\u8eca\u306b\u71b1\u8996\u7dda\u3000\uff19\u6708\u306b\u5f15\u9000\u3057\u305f\u901a\u52e4\u8eca\u4e21\u3001\u30d5\u30a3\u30ea\u30d4\u30f3\u3067\u7b2c\u4e8c\u306e\u4eba\u751f|trans-title=Commuter trains retired in September to live a second life in the Philippines|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120414125037/http://sankei.jp.msn.com/life/news/111126/trd11112612010008-n1.htm|archivedate=April 14, 2012|url-status=dead|accessdate=April 16, 2012}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[203 series]]-derived coaches\n|[[File:01332jfVito_Cruz_railway_station_San_Antonio_Makati_Cityfvf_04.jpg|200px]]\n|[[Kawasaki Heavy Industries]]<br>[[Nippon Sharyo]]<br>\n|1982 (acquired 2011)\n|29 (5 trains)\n|In service<ref name=\"sankei\" />\n|-\n|''INKA coaches''\n|\n| PT INKA\n| 2020\n| 15\n| Under construction<ref name=\"Inquirer-7Trains\" />\n|-\n|}\n\n===Multiple units===\nThe first multiple units in service with the PNR in 1948 were locally-constructed diesel multiple units fitted with Cummins engines, the first ones bulit by Filipinos.<ref name=\"cmi\"/> In 1955, the agency ordered another 20 diesel railcars from Japan. It was later complemented and replaced by the box-shaped CMC units built in 1973. The CMC units were used on the ''Mayon Limited'' and also became the first trains on the ''Pe\u00f1afrancia Express'' service. The inter-city CMCs were replaced by new streamlined ''Pe\u00f1afrancia Express'' trains in the 1980s while it continued to serve on the [[PNR Metro Commuter Line]] until 1999 when it was replaced by Japanese push-pull 7A class coaches.\n\nSince 2009, PNR has acquired several multiple units that were either given second-hand from Japan, or brand new from other countries. This began with the purchase of then brand-new [[PNR Hyundai Rotem DMU|Hyundai Rotem DMUs]].<ref name=\"Specs\" /> This order was followed by several orders of mostly second-hand rolling stock from Japan. In 2018, PNR signed a deal with Indonesian rolling stock manufacturer [[Industri Kereta Api]] (PT INKA) for purchase of another six sets of multiple units. By entering service in 2019, these were officially named the 8000 Class.<ref name=\"Inquirer-7Trains\" /> The Department of Science and Technology also helped in building additional stock through the Hybrid Electric Train (HET). This is the first trainset to be designed by Filipino engineers and the first locally-built multiple units since the 1948 Cummins railmotors.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://techmagus.icu/dost-hybrid-electric-train-inauguration/|title=DOST's Hybrid Electric Train Inauguration|date=April 29, 2019|work=techmagus|accessdate=April 29, 2019}}</ref> It was officially turned over to PNR on June 20, 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://mirdc.dost.gov.ph/2-uncategorised/188-dost-mirdc-turns-over-the-hybrid-electric-train-het-to-the-pnr|title=DOST-MIRDC turns over the Hybrid Electric Train (HET) to the PNR|website=The Official Website of Metals Industry Research and Development Center|language=en-gb|access-date=June 26, 2019}}</ref> The government is currently negotiating with local companies for the HET's mass production.\n\nIn 2019, with the realization of the [[North\u2013South Commuter Railway]] project that has been on hold, PNR ordered thirteen Sustina Commuter electric trains from [[Japan Transport Engineering Company]] (J-TREC) and shall begin operations by 2021.<ref name=\"BWorldOnline-DoTr\" /> The project will be the first part of the system-wide modernization of PNR from narrow gauge and diesel power to standard gauge and electric power that shall happen in the long term.\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+\nMultiple Units\n!Class\n!Image\n!Type\n!Gauge\n!Manufacturer\n!Year Built\n!Top Speed\n!Units Built\n!Status\n|-\n|''Cummins Railmotor''\n|\n|DMU\n|{{Track gauge|1067 mm|lk=on}}\n|MRR\n|1948\n|\n|\n|Decommissioned<ref name=\"cmi\">[https://www.flickr.com/photos/79691913@N05/12693933305/in/pool-1395212@N21/ 1948 0331 New Rail Motor train - Flickr.]</ref>\n|-\n|''Mitsubishi railcars''\n|\n|Diesel [[railcar]]\n|{{Track gauge|1067 mm|lk=on}}\n|[[Mitsubishi Heavy Industries]]<br>Tokyo Car<br>[[Mitsui & Co.|Daichi Bussan]]\n|1955\n|{{Convert|95|km/h|mph|abbr=on}}\n|100 (5 units per train)\n|Decommissioned in 1985<ref>[https://www.flickr.com/photos/goriob1/5075188158/in/pool-1395212@N21/ 1955 1219 New MRR Diesel Cars]</ref><ref>[https://www.flickr.com/photos/goriob1/5067477155/in/pool-1395212@N21/ 1958 0908 MRR New Rail Cars.]</ref>\n|-\n|[[KiHa 52|KiHa 52-100]]\n|[[File:Philippine Railways PNR Ligao Station.jpeg|200px]]\n|[[Diesel multiple unit|DMU]]\n|{{Track gauge|1067 mm|lk=on}}\n|[[Japanese National Railways|JNR]]\n|1962&ndash;66 (acquired 2011)\n|{{Convert|80|km/h|mph|abbr=on}}\n|7 (1/3 cars per set)\n|In service\n|-\n|[[KiHa 35|KiHa 350]]\n|[[File:PNR KiHa350 White.jpg|200px]]\n|DMU\n|{{Track gauge|1067 mm|lk=on}}\n|Fuji Heavy Industries\n|1961-66 (acquired 2011)\n|{{Convert|80|km/h|mph|abbr=on}}\n|6 (2/3/4 cars per set)\n|In service\n|-\n|[[KiHa 59 series|KiHa 59]]\n|[[File:WTNaga STAR B47a.jpg|200px]]\n|DMU\n|{{Track gauge|1067 mm|lk=on}}\n|JNR\n|1967-68<br>1989 (as KiHa 59)<br>(acquired 2011)\n|{{Convert|80|km/h|mph|abbr=on}}\n|3 (3 cars per set)\n|In service<ref name=\"Inquirer-7Trains\" />\n|-\n|''Mayon Limited'' DMU\n|\n|DMU\n|{{Track gauge|1067 mm|lk=on}}\n|JNR\n|1973\n|{{Convert|95|km/h|mph|abbr=on}}\n|16 (8 cars per set)\n|Decommissioned<ref>[https://www.flickr.com/photos/fairlane/4831029248/in/pool-1395212@N21/ 1973 Mayon Express Limited - Flickr.]</ref>\n|-\n|''Mayon Limited'' DMU\n|\n|DMU\n|{{Track gauge|1067 mm|lk=on}}\n|JNR\n|1973\n|{{Convert|95|km/h|mph|abbr=on}}\n|16 (8 cars per set)\n|Decommissioned<ref>[https://www.flickr.com/photos/fairlane/4831029248/in/pool-1395212@N21/ 1973 Mayon Express Limited - Flickr.]</ref>\n|-\n|CMC 300\n|\n|DMU\n|{{Track gauge|1067 mm|lk=on}}\n|JNR\n|1974-76\n|{{Convert|95|km/h|mph|abbr=on}}\n|60\n|Decommissioned in 1999<ref>[https://www.flickr.com/photos/25653307@N03/4224735414/in/pool-1395212@N21/ Philippine National Railways (PNR) Diesel Rail Car set lead by CMC 376 and CMC 374 trailing just south of Buendia Railway Station, Manila, Philippines.]</ref>\n|-\n|''Nikk\u014d''\n|\n|DMU\n|{{Track gauge|1067 mm|lk=on}}\n|JNR\n|1974<br>1998 (Refurbished as IC-888)\n|{{Convert|100|km/h|mph|abbr=on}}\n|26 (2-3 per train)\n|7 units refurbished in 1998 as ''Bicol Express'' T-577.<ref name=\"t577\">[https://www.flickr.com/photos/79691913@N05/8415678709/in/pool-1395212@N21/ 1998 0623 General Manager's Train T-577 - Flickr.]</ref><br>Decommissioned in 2004.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.yumpu.com/en/document/read/37144136/philippine-national-railways-rollingstock-status-aboutphilippinesph |title=Philippine National Railways Rolling Stock Status |publisher=Philippine Railway Historical Society |access-date=March 21, 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[PNR Hyundai Rotem DMU|Hyundai Rotem DMU]]\n|[[File:DMU-06_near_FTI_Station.jpg|200px]]\n|DMU\n|{{Track gauge|1067 mm|lk=on}}\n|[[Hyundai Rotem]]\n|2009-10\n|{{Convert|80|km/h|mph|abbr=on}}\n|18 (3 cars per set)\n|In service<ref name=\"Specs\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.hyundai-rotem.co.kr/Eng/Business/Rail/Business_Record_View.asp?brid=228 |title=Railway Systems-Project Record View |website=www.hyundai-rotem.co.kr |access-date=December 25, 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[DOST Hybrid Electric Train|DOST HET]] (''3000 Class'')\n|[[File:DOST Hybrid Electric Train at the PNR Alabang Station.jpg|200px]]\n|[[Hybrid train|Hybrid]] DMU/[[Battery electric multiple unit|BEMU]]\n|{{Track gauge|1067 mm|lk=on}}\n|[[Department of Science and Technology (Philippines)|DOST\u2013MIRDC]]<br>Fil-Asia Automotive\n|2019-20\n|{{Convert|80|km/h|mph|abbr=on}}\n|5 (5 cars per set)\n|Prototype unit in service, more units in order<ref name=\"pna\">{{cite news |last1=Pa-a |first1=Saul |title=1st Filipino hybrid train runs from Calamba to Manila|url=https://www.pna.gov.ph/articles/1068084 |accessdate= December 18, 2019 |agency=Philippine News Agency |date=April 24, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"pan\">[https://www.carmudi.com.ph/journal/meet-the-first-filipino-built-train-the-hybrid-electric-train-het/ ''Meet the First Filipino-Built Train: The Hybrid Electric Train (HET)'']. Carmudi.com.ph. Retrieved December 18, 2019.</ref>\n|-\n| [[PNR 8000 class|8000]]/ [[PNR 8100 class|8100]]\n|[[File:New_PNR_Cars.jpg|200px]]\n|DMU\n|{{Track gauge|1067 mm|lk=on}}\n|PT INKA\n|2019-20\n|{{Convert|100|km/h|mph|abbr=on}}\n|4 (3/4 cars per set)\n|In service<ref name=\"Inquirer-7Trains\" />\n|-\n|''[[E233 series|E233]]-type [[North\u2013South Commuter Railway|NSCR]] EMUs''\n|\n|[[Electric multiple unit|EMU]]\n|{{Track gauge|1435 mm|lk=on}}\n|[[Japan Transport Engineering Company|J-TREC]]\n|2021\n|{{Convert|120|km/h|mph|abbr=on}}\n|104 (8 cars per set)\n|On order<ref name=\"BWorldOnline-DoTr\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.bworldonline.com/dotr-prepares-to-award-rolling-stock-contract/|title=DoTr prepares to award rolling stock contract {{!}} BusinessWorld|last=Charm|first=Neil|language=en-US|access-date=December 18, 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n|''CRRC Intercity DMUs''\n|\n|DMU\n|{{Track gauge|1435 mm|lk=on}}\n|[[CRRC Zhuzhou Locomotive]]\n|2021\n|{{Convert|160|km/h|mph|abbr=on}}<ref name=\"rap\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.rappler.com/newsbreak/fact-check/243130-pnr-bicol-express-reopened-september |title=FALSE: PNR Bicol Express 'reopened' September 2019 |website=Rappler |access-date=December 25, 2018}}</ref>\n|9 (3 cars per set)\n|On order<ref name=\"crrc\">{{Cite web|url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/business/12/18/19/chinese-firm-signs-contract-to-supply-trains-for-pnr-bicol-project|title=Chinese firm signs contract to supply trains for PNR Bicol project|access-date=December 23, 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n|}\n\n==Liveries==\nThe Manila-Dagupan Railway, the Manila Railroad Company and the Philippine National Railways sported various liveries representing various eras of the company, usually to celebrate the arrival of new rolling stock. Each of these are painted by hand.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.flickr.com/photos/46273205@N02/5796451721|title=GEDC2105|website=Flickr|access-date=March 16, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Steam locomotive era (1892-1954)===\nThere were no available colored images of Manila-Dagupan Railway and the Manila Railroad Company's rolling stock before the war so the color scheme of the carriages remains unknown. However, based on the surviving locomotives, the steam locomotives owned by the two companies sported a black-only livery like most of the notable American steam engines.<ref name=\"is\"/>\n\n===Railmotor livery (1948)===\nThe Cummins railmotors were colored black or white, and orange. The pre-war carriages salvaged and refurbished in the late 1940s also used this color scheme.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.flickr.com/photos/36157525@N02/4540997038/in/photolist-7VgNdo|title=MotorTrain-1|access-date=March 16, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===MRR/PNR livery (1955)===\n[[File:PNR Logo.png|thumbnail|upright=0.9|right|Monogram of the PNR used in the 1960s. The modern PNR seal altered its colors to blue and orange.]]\nThe MRR celebrated the arrival of its first diesel rolling stock with its colors changed to dark green and yellow, or alternately to yellow-orange and dark green. The livery was retained when the Philippine government took over and renamed it the Philippine National Railways. During the transition to PNR, the old MRR monogram with a diamond-shaped seal was painted out and the PNR circular seal and monogram was placed on the front of the cab with yellow wing-like symbols outside it. The PNR acronym is also placed on the sides as well.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.flickr.com/photos/intervene/4495939839 |title=1978 LOCO No. 901|website=Flickr|access-date=March 16, 2020}}</ref> By the 1980s, the diesel multiple units will have a yellow body and the wing-like symbols are colored dark green.\n\n===Commuter Motor Coach livery (c. 1978)===\nDuring the late 1970s, the Commuter Motor Coaches used on PNR's local train services in Metro Manila and the Bicol Region was colored white and navy blue.<ref>{{Cite web|title=1980 PNR TO CARMONA|url=https://www.flickr.com/photos/intervene/3473134160|website=Flickr|accessdate=March 16, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Metrotren livery (1990)===\nWhen President [[Corazon Aquino]] inaugurated the rebranded [[PNR Metro Commuter Line|Manila commuter service]] as \"Metrotren\" in 1990, the CMC coaches were repainted to navy blue, white and red. This was also used for the 1998 restocking of the ''Bicol Express'' with the old ''Pe\u00f1afrancia Express'' IC-888 train. This was used until the mid 2000s when both multiple unit types were changed to the navy blue livery.<ref>{{Cite web|title=06649 (228) 04-02-1990 Philippine National Railways (PNR) in the yard outside the workshops I building with a Metrotren carriage in Kaloocan City, Manila, Philippines. |url=https://www.flickr.com/photos/25653307@N03/3696525933/|access-date=March 16, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Philippines 2000 livery (1997)===\nThe [[GE Universal Series]]-based 900, 2500 and 5000 classes sported a red livery celebrating Fidel Ramos' [[Philippines 2000]] program.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.flickr.com/photos/14564368@N02/33599106536/|title=908 Tayuman|access-date=March 16, 2020.}}</ref> Although the PNR revised this livery after 2000, some retained it due to lack of maintenance funds and a 900 class survived with this livery in use until 2008. Some of the freight carriages had the Philippines 2000 name spray-painted on top the old green and yellow livery.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.flickr.com/photos/79691913@N05/8535627223|title=1999 0318 PNR Philippines 2000.}}</ref>\n\n===Navy blue livery (c. 2000, 2011)===\n[[File:921 at Sucat, Muntinlupa.png|thumbnail|left|DEL 921 and 203-series coach sporting the 2011-type navy blue livery.]]\nA navy blue livery was introduced after the expiry of the Philippines 2000 program. This followed after PNR acquired locomotive-hauled 12 and 14 series coaches from Japan. There are subtle differences with the coaches used on the ''Commuter Express'' (formerly ''Metrotren'') and the ''Bicol Express''. The ''Commuter Express'' trainsets were navy blue with orange highlights while the ''Bicol Express'' were navy blue with gold highlights. The PNR symbol on the ''Commuter Express'' was white while on the ''Bicol Express'' was gold. The locomotives' colors were also changed to navy blue and orange.\n\nThis livery was re-introduced in 2011 although it was not used on the ''Bicol Express'' trainsets.\n{{-}}\n\n===Filtrack livery (2009)===\nPNR attempted to revitalize the ''Bicol Express'' in 2009 with the support of president [[Gloria Macapagal Arroyo]]. This was supported with a change of logo and liveries. The coaches in PNR service used white and orange while the locomotives' cabs were colored white while the PNR monogram logo was sealed out. The trains also sported the \"Filtrack\" brand on the coaches and on the side of the locomotives. However, this was short lived after the ''Bicol Express'' stopped its services indefinitely. By 2015, all of the rolling stock followed the 2000s navy blue livery.\n\n===INKA livery (2019)===\n[[File:INKA-8101_near_FTI_Station.jpg|thumbnail|left|An INKA-built [[PNR 8100 class]] with the new livery]].\nThe PNR announced another logo change and changes to its livery in 2019. This is after the [[Presidency of Rodrigo Duterte|Duterte administration]] under the [[Department of Transportation (Philippines)|Department of Transportation]] announced major reforms to the PNR. The PNR's monogram is now fully incorporated on a [[Seal (emblem)|seal]]-type logo, bearing the agency's name and the year it was founded. The seal was also changed from orange and blue to golden yellow and navy blue. At the same time, the rolling stock also changed its liveries with regards to the arrival of the new rolling stock from Indonesia. The [[203 series]]-based passenger cars' liveries did not change as of 2020.\n\nThe first among the old rolling stock was the [[KiHa 35]]0 and [[KiHa 59 series]] trains. After this was the Hyundai Rotem DMUs and finally, 900 series locomotive DEL 917 changed its livery to orange, similar to the upcoming CC300s. All multiple units were fitted with new windows to resist stoning. The colors however varied from one type of rolling stock to another but the common theme was the inclusion of orange (as the highlight color), white (as the main stock color), navy blue (as the side line color) and black (as the bottom color).\n\n===CRRC diesel multiple unit livery (2021)===\nThe latest effort to the revitalization of the South Main Line, particularly the ''Bicol Express'' intercity service, was unveiled in 2019 dubbed the \"South Long Haul\" project. A scale model of the train that will be used was revealed during a contract signing ceremony between the Philippine National Railways, its superior agency the Department of Transportation, and the Chinese rolling stock manufacturer CRRC Zhuzhou Locomotive. The three-car train will also feature a red-orange livery with black stripes on its windows. This train is set to arrive by 2021.\n\n{{-}}\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Transportation|Railways|Philippines}}\n* [[Department of Transportation (Philippines)|Department of Transportation]]\n* [[List of Philippine National Railways stations]]\n* [[Panay Railways]]\n* [[Rail transport in the Philippines]]\n* [[Strong Republic Transit System]]\n\n==Notes==\n:{{Note|a}} Inter-city and freight services have been suspended since 2016. The [[North\u2013South Commuter Railway]] will be the first intercity service since the discontinuation of the ''Bicol Express'' in 2016. Construction of the line commenced in 2019. There are also plans to revitalize to freight service. See [[Philippine National Railways#Freight revival|Freight revival]] for more information.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n===Further reading===\n* Uranza, Rogelio. (2002). [https://web.archive.org/web/20091229002413/http://www.cleanairnet.org/caiasia/1412/articles-37345_tp_20_uranza.pdf ''The Role of Traffic Engineering and Management in Metro Manila'']. Workshop paper presented in the Regional Workshop: Transport Planning, Demand Management and Air Quality, February 2002, Manila, Philippines. Asian Development Bank (ADB).\n* {{Cite web\n|url=http://www-wds.worldbank.org/external/default/WDSContentServer/WDSP/IB/2001/06/27/000094946_01060804031083/Rendered/PDF/multi0page.pdf\n|author=World Bank\n|title=Project Appraisal Document for the Metro Manila Urban Transport Integration Project\n|publisher=World Bank\n|date=May 23, 2001}}\n\n* [http://www.jica.go.jp Japan International Cooperation Agency Official Page] \"Revitalization of Main Line South Project(1989)\"\n* [https://www.facebook.com/ANCalerts/videos/10154331805488791/?hc_location=ufi List of stations of East West line]\n* [http://www.gmanetwork.com/news/money/economy/629155/east-west-rail-manila-bay-flood-control-projects-up-for-icc-approval/story/?just_in East West line for icc approval]\n* [http://megawide.com.ph/wp-content/uploads/2017/07/Megawide-Confirms-Participation-in-Railway-Project.pdf Statement from Megawide company]\n* [https://ppp.gov.ph/?ppp_projects=east-west-rail-project East West line the PPP Projects]\n* [http://news.abs-cbn.com/business/07/13/17/megawide-joins-quezon-city-to-manila-railway-project Megawide Joins Quezon City to Manila railway project]\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n* [http://www.pnr.gov.ph Philippine National Railways (official website)]\n* [http://www.facebook.com/pnrailways Official Facebook page of Philippine National Railways]\n* [https://www.facebook.com/philippinerailways Facebook page of Philippine Railways]\n* [https://twitter.com/philrailways Twitter page of Philippine Railways]\n* [https://www.facebook.com/groups/120989042040/ Facebook for Philippine Railway Historical Society]\n\n{{PNR Rolling Stocks}}\n{{SRTS}}\n{{Department of Transportation and Communications}}\n{{Transportation in the Philippines}}\n{{Rolling Stock of the Philippines}}\n\n[[Category:Philippine National Railways| ]]\n[[Category:Department of Transportation (Philippines)]]\n[[Category:Government-owned and controlled corporations of the Philippines]]\n[[Category:Railway companies of the Philippines]]\n[[Category:Rail transportation in Metro Manila]]\n[[Category:Transportation in Luzon]]\n[[Category:Philippine brands]]\n[[Category:3 ft 6 in gauge railways in the Philippines]]\n[[Category:Railway lines opened in 1892]]\n[[Category:1892 establishments in the Philippines]]\n[[Category:Spanish colonial infrastructure in the Philippines]]\n", "text_old": "{{distinguish|Panay Railways{{!}}Philippine Railway Company}}\n{{short description|Railway company in the Philippines}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name     = Philippine National Railways <br /> {{small|{{native name|fil|Pambansang Daambakal ng Pilipinas|icon=no}}}}\n| logo     = Philippine National Railways (PNR).svg\n| foundation       = November 24, 1892 <small>(as Ferrocarril de Manila-Dagupan)</small><br>June 20, 1964 <small>(as Philippine National Railways)</small>\n| location_city    = [[Manila]]\n| location_country = [[Philippines]]\n| area_served      = [[Metro Manila]]<br>[[Calabarzon]]<br>[[Bicol Region]]\n| key_people       = Roberto T. Lastimoso [[Chairman]]<br>Junn Magno, General Manager\n| industry         = [[Rail transport]]\n| products         = \n| services         = '''Current''':<br>[[Commuter rail]]<br>'''Suspended'''{{Ref label|a|a}}:<br>[[Inter-city rail]]<br> [[Rail freight transport|Freight services]]\n| revenue          = \n| operating_income = \n| net_income       = \n| assets           = \n| equity           = \n| owner            = [[Government of the Philippines]] under [[Department of Transportation (Philippines)|DOTr]]\n| num_employees    = \n| divisions        = \n| website          = {{URL|http://www.pnr.gov.ph|pnr.gov.ph}}\n}}\n\nThe '''Philippine National Railways''' also known as ('''PNR''') ({{lang-fil|Pambansang Daambakal ng Pilipinas}} and {{lang-es|Ferrocarril Nacional de Filipinas}}) is a [[government-owned and controlled corporation|state-owned]] [[railway company]] in the [[Philippines]], operating a single line of track on [[Luzon]]. As of 2016, it operates one [[commuter rail]] service in [[Metro Manila]] and local services between [[Sipocot, Camarines Sur|Sipocot]], [[Naga, Camarines Sur|Naga City]] and [[Legazpi, Albay|Legazpi City]] in the [[Bicol Region]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.pnr.gov.ph/getting-around/metro-commuter-line/fares-tickets |title=Fares & Tickets|accessdate=October 31, 2016}}</ref> PNR began operations on November 24, 1892 as the '''Ferrocarril de Manila-Dagupan''', during the [[History of the Philippines (1521\u20131898)|Spanish colonial period]], and later becoming the '''Manila Railroad Company''' (MRR) during the [[History of the Philippines (1898\u20131946)|American colonial period]]. It became the Philippine National Railways on June 20, 1964 by virtue of Republic Act No. 4156. The PNR is an agency of the [[Department of Transportation (Philippines)|Department of Transportation]].\n\nPNR used to operate over {{convert|1100|km|mi|0|abbr=on}} of route from [[La Union]] to the [[Bicol Region]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://opinion.inquirer.net/74466/sad-saga-of-pnr|title=Sad saga of PNR|publisher=Inquirer.net|date=May 13, 2014|accessdate=July 29, 2014}}</ref> However, neglect reduced PNR's service. Persistent problems with informal settlers in the 1990s contributed further to PNR's decline. In 2006, [[Typhoon Xangsane|Typhoons Milenyo]] and [[Typhoon Durian|Reming]] caused severe damage to the network, resulting in the suspension of the Manila-Bicol services.  In 2007 the Philippine government initiated a rehabilitation project aiming to remove informal settlers from the PNR [[right of way]], revitalize commuter services in Metro Manila, and restore the Manila-Bicol route as well as lost services in Northern Luzon. In July 2009, PNR unveiled a new corporate identity and inaugurated new [[rolling stock]].  Long-distance Bicol services resumed in June 2011, but were suspended again in October 2012, leaving only local service between Naga and Sipocot.<ref name=\"auto1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.philstar.com/business/2013/12/29/1272906/bicol-express-revival-hinges-safety-issues|title=Bicol Express revival hinges on safety issues|date=December 29, 2013|accessdate=October 31, 2016}}</ref> Local service between Naga and Legazpi resumed in October 2015.<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web |url=https://www.silent-gardens.com/blog/bicol-express-open/ |title=Train: Naga to Legazpi open! Soon again Bicol Express?|date=September 9, 2015|accessdate=October 31, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n[[File:Ferrocarril Manila-Dagupan 1885.jpg|thumbnail|Passengers posing in front of the \"Ferrocarril de Manila y Dagupan\" (c. 1885).]]\n\n===Spanish period===\nOn June 25, 1875, under a royal decree issued by [[King of Spain|King]] [[Alfonso XII of Spain|Alfonso XII]] of Spain, the required Inspector of Public Works of the Philippine Islands was requested to submit a railway system plan for [[Luzon]]. The plan, which was submitted five months later by Don Eduardo Lopez Navarro, was entitled ''Memoria Sobre el Plan General de Ferrocarriles en la Isla de Luz\u00f3n'', and was promptly approved. A concession for the construction of a railway line from [[Manila]] to [[Dagupan City|Dagupan]] was granted to Don Edmundo Sykes of the Ferrocarril de Manila\u2013Dagupan (Manila\u2013Dagupan Railway), later to become the Manila Railway Company, Ltd. of London, on June 1, 1887.<ref name=\"PNR history\">{{cite web|url=http://pnr.gov.ph/history.htm |title=Brief history of PNR |publisher=Philippine National Railways (February 27, 2009) |accessdate=November 4, 2011<!-->at [[Internet Archive]]<--> |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090227040648/http://pnr.gov.ph/history.htm |archivedate=February 27, 2009 }}</ref><ref name=\"NHCP\">{{cite web|title=Manila Railroad Company|url=http://nhcphistoricsites.blogspot.com/2011/11/manila-railroad-company.html|work=National Register of Historic Sites & Structures in the Philippines|publisher=[[National Historical Commission of the Philippines]]|accessdate=September 6, 2013}}</ref>\n\nThe Ferrocarril de Manila\u2013Dagupan, which constitutes much of the North Main Line today, began construction on July 31, 1887 with the laying of the cornerstone for [[Tutuban railway station|Tutuban station]], and the {{convert|195|km|mi|adj=on|sp=us}} line opened on November 24, 1892.  Expansion of the Philippine railway network would not begin until the [[History of the Philippines (1898\u20131946)|American colonial period]], when on December 8, 1902, the [[Philippine Commission]] passed legislation authorizing the construction of another railway line, which would later form the South Main Line.\n\n===American period===\n[[File:Manila Railway Company 1907.jpg|thumbnail|upright=0.8|left|Bond of the Manila Railway Company Ltd, issued 10. May 1907]]\n[[File:Philippine_railways_during_its_peak.jpg|thumb|Manila Railroad Company during its peak. Map contains lines that are presently inactive.]]\n[[File:PNR17-Dagupan.jpg|thumb|Type [[0-4-4]] Manila Railroad Company Locomotive #17 on display at the [[Dagupan|Dagupan City]] Museum.]]\nAdditional legislation was passed in 1909 authorizing further railway construction and the use of government bonds to finance them, and by 1916, {{convert|792.5|km|mi|sp=us}} of track had been built by the company, which had reorganized itself as the Manila Railroad Company of New Jersey (MRR).<ref name=\"survey1951\">{{cite report | title=Report of Survey of the Manila Railroad Company and the Preliminary Survey of Railroads for Mindanao | chapter=Chapter I: Present Conditions | pages=1\u201312 | publisher=De Leuw, Cather & Company | location=Chicago | year=1951 }}</ref> Apart from the North and South Main Lines, other lines branching out of these two main lines were built, like the lines to Rosales and San Quintin, Pangasinan; San Jose and Cabanatuan, Nueva Ecija; Dau, Carmen, Floridablanca and Arayat, all in Pampanga province, as well as inside the US Air Base Fort Stotsenburg which became Clark Air Base; Antipolo, Taytay, and Montalban, a spur line to Nielsen Field in what is now Ayala Avenue in the Makati Financial District from Culi Culi (now Pasay Road) Station, all in Rizal province; Cavite City and the nearby US Air Base of Sangley Point as well as Noveleta and Naic, both in Cavite province; Canlubang, Santa Cruz and Pagsanjan all in Laguna province; Batangas City and Bauan both in Batangas province, as well as a line connecting San Pablo City in Laguna to Luta (later Malvar) in Batangas province (this used to be part of Main Line South until a shorter cut-off line connecting Los Banos on the Santa-Cruz/Pangsanjan line to San Pablo was opened); Port Ragay in the Bicol province of Camarines Sur; as well as till Tabaco from Legaspi, Albay.\n\nSimilar to other railroads at the time, the Manila Railroad Company suffered from financial difficulties during [[World War I]], and on February 4, 1916, the [[Philippine Assembly]] passed Act No. 2574, authorizing the [[Governor-General of the Philippines|Governor-General]] to negotiate for the nationalization of the MRR's assets.  The MRR was eventually nationalized in January 1917, with the Philippine government paying \u20b18 million to the company's owners and assuming \u20b153.9 million in outstanding debt. Consequently, the MRR's management shifted from British to American hands, and in 1923, Jos\u00e9 Paez became the first Filipino general manager.<ref name=\"survey1951\" />\n\nDuring the 1920s, the MRR embarked on a general program of improvements as a result of operating surpluses accrued over much of the decade.  The \u20b130 million program allowed for the extension of railway service on the North Main Line from Dagupan to [[San Fernando, La Union|San Fernando]] in [[La Union]], the extension of the South Main Line to [[Legazpi, Albay|Legazpi]] in [[Albay]], and the construction of several spur lines. The last rail connecting Manila to Bicol was laid on November 17, 1937 and regular direct service between Manila and Legazpi was inaugurated on May 8, 1938, and by 1941, the MRR operated {{convert|1140.5|km|mi|sp=us}} of track.<ref name=\"survey1951\" />\n\nOn December 14, 1941, at the start of [[World War II]], the MRR was put under U.S. military control, and on December 30, the MRR management was ordered to allow U.S. military forces to destroy network infrastructure, resulting in very extensive damage to train facilities and right of way.  Coupled with further damage during the [[Japanese occupation of the Philippines]], where the [[Imperial Japanese Army]] operated services on a very limited basis using whatever could be salvaged, and further fighting in the [[Philippines Campaign (1944\u201345)|Allied liberation of the Philippines]] by the combined American and Filipino forces a few years later, damages to railroad property amounted to around \u20b130 million.<ref name=\"survey1951\" />  By the end of the war, only {{convert|452|km|mi|sp=us}} were operational,<ref name=\"PNR history\" /> largely as a result of the [[United States Army]] and the [[Philippine Commonwealth Army]] performing temporary repairs on railroad infrastructure for military purposes.  MRR property was later returned to the Philippine government on February 1, 1946.<ref name=\"survey1951\" />\n\n===Post-war period===\nFollowing the war, the MRR was able to restore limited services, using surplus military equipment and payments made by the United States Army and the Philippine Commonwealth Army for use of railway facilities in the Philippines Campaign.  By July 1, 1947, funded by a \u20b120 million rehabilitation allocation set aside by the Philippine government, around 75% of the entire railway network prior to 1941 was rehabilitated.  By 1951, with the MRR receiving \u20b13 million in war reparations funds, {{convert|941.9|km|mi|sp=us}} of track, representing 82.5% of the total railway network prior to 1941, was in operation.<ref name=\"survey1951\" />  Later in the 1950s, the MRR fleet of locomotives was converted from steam to [[diesel engine]]s, and the company was given a new charter under [[List of Philippine laws|Republic Act No. 4156]], becoming the modern-day Philippine National Railways.\n\n===Creation of PNR===\nNatural calamities such as the 1973 and 1975 floods disrupted services and forced the closure of several parts of the main lines. On July 23, 1979, President [[Ferdinand Marcos]] issued Executive Order No. 546, which designated the Philippine National Railways as an attached agency of the then [[Department of Transportation (Philippines)|Department of Transportation and Communications]].<ref name=\"PNR history\" />\n\nIn 1988, during the administration of [[Corazon Aquino]], the North main line was closed, with trains unable to reach various [[provinces of the Philippines|provinces]] in the country. The South main line was also closed due to typhoons and floods, and the eruption of [[Mayon|Mayon Volcano]] in 1993, in which ash flows and lava destroyed the rail line and its facilities. However, jeeps, buses and taxis were popular, and many people were swayed from the present service until 2009.\n\nWhen Fidel V. Ramos succeeded Corazon Aquino, he decided to rehabilitate the South Main Line from Tutuban to Legaspi, and appointed Jose B. Dado as the new PNR general manager. A railway system running from Manila to Clark was also set to be constructed in the 1990s, when Ramos signed a memorandum of agreement with [[Juan Carlos I of Spain]] for its construction in September 1994, but the project was later cancelled due to disagreement on the source of funding.<ref name=\"ABSCBN-NorthRailTimeline\">{{cite web|url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/nation/07/15/08/track-northrail-timeline|title=Off track: Northrail timeline|last=News|first=ABS-CBN|website=ABS-CBN News|access-date=February 17, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Contemporary history===\n====Rehabilitation attempts and the NorthRail project====\n{{See also|North\u2013South Commuter Railway#NorthRail project}}\nThe administration of [[Gloria Macapagal-Arroyo]] actively pursued the rehabilitation of the Philippine National Railways through various investments and projects designed to revive Philippine rail transport,<ref name=\"PNR history\" /><ref name=\"southrail\" /><ref name=\"pnr-rehab\">{{cite news |title=PNR rail rehabilitation to start September |first=Riza T. |last=Olchondra |url=http://business.inquirer.net/money/topstories/view_article.php?article_id=61814 |archive-url=https://archive.is/20130221155141/http://business.inquirer.net/money/topstories/view_article.php?article_id=61814 |url-status=dead |archive-date=February 21, 2013 |newspaper=[[Philippine Daily Inquirer]] |location=Manila |date=April 22, 2007 |accessdate=April 28, 2010 |quote=The Philippine National Railways (PNR) will start repairing and improving its North and South railways by September, PNR General Manager Jose Ma. Sarasola II said Friday. }}</ref> despite the numerous problems involved. Total reconstruction of rail bridges and tracks, including replacement of the current 35-kilogram (77-pound) track with newer 50-kilogram (110-pound) tracks<ref name=\"pnr-rehab\" /> and the refurbishing of stations, were part of the rehabilitation and expansion process. The first phase, converting all the lines of the [[Metro Manila|Manila metropolitan area]], were completed in 2009.<ref name=\"pnr-rehab\" /> On July 14, 2009, [[Gloria Macapagal-Arroyo]] presided over the launch of the new [[diesel multiple unit]]s from [[Hyundai Rotem]] for the Philippine National Railways. As part of its new image, a new brand name, ''PNR Filtrack'' was added and a new PNR logo was unveiled until the succeeding administration decided to revert to the original logo.<ref name=\"bicol-commuter\" />\n\nThe San Cristobal bridge in Calamba, Laguna was rebuilt in May 2011. The Bicol Express train service was inaugurated on June 29, with a maiden voyage between Manila and [[Naga, Camarines Sur|Naga City]] plus a return trip back to the terminus on July 1. This inaugural trip was marred by the collapse of the embankment at Malaguico, Sipocot. It was discovered before the train passed through and was repaired. The restored Bicol Express intercity service was offered on a daily basis, running mostly during night time.\n\nThe Northrail project involved the upgrading of the existing single track to an elevated dual-track system, converting the [[Track gauge|rail gauge]] from [[narrow gauge]] to [[standard gauge]], and linking Manila to [[Malolos|Malolos City]] in [[Bulacan]] and further on to [[Angeles, Philippines|Angeles City]], [[Clark Special Economic Zone]], the [[Clark International Airport]]. The railway project was contracted out by the Arroyo administration in 2003 to China National Machinery and Equipment Corporation (CNMEC) for an original cost of $421 million.<ref name=\"ABSCBN-NorthRail\">{{Cite web|url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/nation/07/15/08/track-northrail-timeline|title=Off track: Northrail timeline|last=News|first=ABS-CBN|website=ABS-CBN News|access-date=February 17, 2019}}</ref> This project was estimated to cost around US$500&nbsp;million, with China offering to provide some US$400&nbsp;million in concessionary financing.<ref name=\"northrail-cost\">{{cite news | url = http://www.lrta.gov.ph/news/news_item_040604_RpChinaBreakGroundForManila-IlocosRailway.htm | title = RP, China break ground for Manila-Ilocos railway | newspaper = [[Malaya (newspaper)|Malaya]] | date = April 6, 2004 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20100509062704/http://www.lrta.gov.ph/news/news_item_040604_RpChinaBreakGroundForManila-IlocosRailway.htm | archivedate = May 9, 2010 | df = mdy-all }}</ref> Construction of the railway was halted, then temporarily continued in January 2009, and then stopped again in March 2011, due to a series of anomalies with the foreign contractor,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pcij.org/blog/2005/09/29/up-study-finds-north-rail-contract-illegal-diadvantageous-to-government|title=U.P. study finds North Rail contract illegal, disadvantageous to government|publisher=The PCIJ Blog|date=September 9, 2005|accessdate=July 29, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140812191628/http://pcij.org/blog/2005/09/29/up-study-finds-north-rail-contract-illegal-diadvantageous-to-government|archive-date=August 12, 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref> before finally being scrapped in 2011 by the Aquino administration on lingering legal issues and corruption allegations.\n\nThe [[Department of Transportation (Philippines)|DOTC]] has examined reviving the project by commissioning a feasibility study by CPCS Transcom Ltd. of Canada. Part of the study examined having a Malolos-Tutuban-Calamba-Los Ba\u00f1os Commuter Line.<ref><http://www.abs-cbnnews.com/business/07/22/13/dotc-eyes-elevated-railway-malolos-los-banos</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://manilastandardtoday.com/2013/10/31/govt-eyes-elevated-rail-project-in-luzon/|title=Govt eyes elevated rail project in Luzon|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140102193828/http://manilastandardtoday.com/2013/10/31/govt-eyes-elevated-rail-project-in-luzon/|archivedate=January 2, 2014|url-status=dead|accessdate=January 1, 2014}}</ref>\n\n====Current developments====\n[[File:PNR NSCR Balagtas Station.jpg|thumb|The future Balagtas station]] \nThe current administration under [[Rodrigo Duterte]] is working towards the rehabilitation of the PNR, the establishment of a railway from [[New Clark City]] to [[Metro Manila]], the [[North\u2013South Commuter Railway|North-South Commuter Railway]],<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.rappler.com/business/173929-manila-clark-railway-stations-revealed-dotr|title=17 stations of Manila-Clark Railway announced|work=Rappler|access-date=August 1, 2018|language=en}}</ref> the reconstruction of the current South Commuter line, and the reestablishment of long-haul services to the south. Rehabilitation of tracks and stations has commenced.\n\nAfter nearly 20 years, PNR reopened the Metro North Commuter line, and launched the Caloocan-Dela Rosa shuttle line, on August 1, 2018.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.gmanetwork.com/news/news/metro/662595/dotr-sees-10-000-passengers-taking-pnr-s-reopened-caloocan-dela-rosa-line/story/|title=20 YEARS AFTER: DOTr sees 10,000 passengers taking PNR's reopened Caloocan-Dela Rosa line|work=GMA News Online|access-date=August 1, 2018|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://news.abs-cbn.com/business/07/31/18/after-20-years-pnrs-caloocan-to-makati-line-to-reopen|title=After 20 years, PNR's Caloocan to Makati line to reopen|last=News|first=ABS-CBN|work=ABS-CBN News|access-date=August 1, 2018|language=en-US}}</ref> This would be followed by a steady expansion and reintroduction of rail services to the north, currently reaching to Malabon City, which has not seen rail activity for nearly 20 years. A plan to reactivate the Carmona line was bared as well,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/DOTrPH/posts/1186365421502592|title=Department of Transportation - Philippines|website=www.facebook.com|language=en|access-date=October 12, 2018}}</ref> and the revival of cargo rail from Port Area, Manila to Laguna is now being planned.<ref name=\"Facebook-DOTrPH\" /><ref name=\"Inquirer-FreightService\">{{Cite news|url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/974414/pnr-to-offer-freight-service-soon|title=PNR to offer freight service soon|last=Yee|first=Jovic|access-date=October 12, 2018|language=en}}</ref>\n\nOn December 16, 2018, all commuter services saw changes in train runs<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.facebook.com/pnrofficialpage/photos/a.247872075258165/2221142151264471/ |title = Philippine National Railways}}</ref> and establishments of new termini, particularly in the recently revived Metro North Commuter. More train runs were added for the north currently terminating at [[Governor Pascual railway station|Governor Pascual]].<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.facebook.com/pnrofficialpage/posts/2221195757925777 | title=Philippine National Railways}}</ref>\n\nOn November 16, 2018, PNR became a provisional member of [[International Union of Railways]].<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.facebook.com/DOTrPH/photos/a.132771066862038/1302675416538258/ |title = Department of Transportation - Philippines}}</ref>\n\nOn May 21, 2019, DMCI won the contract for the construction of PNR North 1.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/money/companies/695159/dmci-japanese-partner-bag-p54-b-contract-for-north-south-commuter-railway-project/story/ |title = DMCI, Japanese partner bag P54-B contract for North-South Commuter Railway project}}</ref>\n\nOn June 14, 2019, PNR became ISO-certified (ISO 9001:2015) for railway repair, rehabilitation, restoration and maintenance, train control and rolling stock maintenance, station operation and other related services. The certification was announced October 2, 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://tribune.net.ph/index.php/2019/10/02/pnr-chugs-way-to-global-standards/|title=PNR chugs way to global standards|first=Sundy|last=Locus|date=October 1, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Operations and services==\nThe PNR currently operates in [[Metro Manila]] and the neighboring [[Laguna (province)|Laguna]] province. At the last years of regular intercity service along the system's entire length in the late 1980s, it served from Tutuban to [[San Fernando, La Union]] on the North Main Line and [[Legazpi, Albay]] on the South Main Line. Various branch lines also led to [[Batangas]], [[Cavite]], [[Nueva Ecija]], [[Rizal]] and [[Tarlac]]. One of the branch lines that led to Carmona was intended to be reopened by 2019. This was not realized as of March 2020.\n\n===Summary of services===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! Service\n! colspan=\"2\" | Terminus\n! Status\n|-\n| rowspan=\"4\" | Metro South Commuter (MSC)\n| Tutuban\n| Alabang\n| {{Operational}}\n|-\n| Tutuban\n| Mamatid\n| {{Operational}}\n|-\n| Tutuban\n| Calamba\n| {{Operational}}\n|-\n| Tutuban\n| IRRI (UP Los Ba\u00f1os)\n| {{Operational}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |Metro North Commuter (MNC)\n| Tutuban\n| Governor Pascual\n| {{Operational}}\n|-\n| Tutuban\n| Valenzuela\n| {{Planned}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"6\" | Shuttle Service (SS)\n| Governor Pascual\n| FTI\n| {{Operational}}\n|-\n| Valenzuela\n| FTI\n| {{Planned}}\n|-\n| Dela Rosa\n| Carmona\n| {{Planned}}\n|-\n| Tutuban\n| Sucat\n| Discontinued\n|-\n| Santa Mesa\n| Sucat\n| Discontinued\n|-\n| Alabang\n| Calamba\n| {{Planned}}\n|-\n| Premiere Train\n| Tutuban\n| Mamatid\n| Discontinued\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\" | Bicol Commuter (BCT)\n| Tagkawayan\n| Naga\n| Suspended\n|-\n| Sipocot\n| Naga\n|{{Operational}}\n|-\n| Naga\n| Legazpi\n| {{Operational}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" | Bicol Express (BEx)\n| Tutuban\n| Naga\n| Suspended\n|-\n| Tutuban\n| Ligao\n| Suspended\n|-\n| Mayon Limited Deluxe (MLD)\n| Tutuban\n| Ligao\n| Discontinued; replaced by ILE\n|-\n| Mayon Limited Ordinary (MLO)\n| Tutuban\n| Ligao\n| Discontinued; replaced by ILE\n|-\n| Isarog Limited Express (ILE)\n| Tutuban\n| Naga\n| Suspended\n|}\n\n===Metro Commuter Line===\n{{main|PNR Metro Commuter Line}}\n\n====''Metro North Commuter''====\nThe reactivated ''Metro North Commuter'' ran initially from Caloocan to Makati and uses a single special fare matrix of PHP 12.00 for ordinary, and PHP 15.00 for air-conditioned. This was later extended to reach FTI in Taguig, now with a distance-based fare matrix. A Caloocan-Tutuban shuttle service also exists, using the original right-of-way once used for the Dagupan line. Originally terminating at [[10th Avenue railway station|10th Avenue station]] while the historical Caloocan station was still being prepared for activation,<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.facebook.com/DOTrPH/posts/1171751846297283 | title=Department of Transportation - Philippines}}</ref> the station now terminates at its originally intended station since September 10.\n\nDOTr and PNR are also working on reviving and reactivating rail services in areas prepared for NorthRail, such as Malabon and possibly Valenzuela. First proposed and planned last September 2018,<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.facebook.com/DOTrPH/posts/1196688110470323 | title=Department of Transportation - Philippines}}</ref> the extension to Gov. Pascual Avenue and the re-establishment of the [[Governor Pascual railway station|Governor Pascual Station]] (formerly called Acacia Station) in Malabon has been done, with new rail ties and narrow gauge rail tracks being restored.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.facebook.com/pnrofficialpage/posts/2119205864791434 | title=Philippine National Railways}}</ref> It reopened to the public on December 3, 2018.\n\nAnother extension, this time targeting Valenzuela City (likely Polo area) has been bared on August 14, 2019, and will require rebuilding a railroad bridge crossing Tullahan river that has been previously destroyed.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.pna.gov.ph/articles/1077844 | title=Completed railway assets to ease traffic by 25%: DOTr}}</ref>\n\nThe line is provisional and services will be potentially interrupted when the elevated tracks are to be constructed, likely after the construction of NLEX Segment 10.1. The reconstructed lines are targeted for freight use as well as part of the system's extension to the north.\n\n====''Metro South Commuter''====\nThe ''Metro Commuter'' (also known by then-remaining active service ''MSC'' or ''Metro South Commuter''),<ref name=\"metrocommuter\">{{cite web |url=http://www.pnr.gov.ph/commuter.htm |title=Metro Commuter |publisher=Philippine National Railways |accessdate=June 8, 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110317015317/http://www.pnr.gov.ph/commuter.htm |archivedate=March 17, 2011  }}</ref> which was formerly called ''Commuter Express ''(also ''Commex''), serves as the [[commuter rail]] service for the [[Metro Manila|Manila metropolitan area]], extending as far south as [[Calamba, Laguna|Calamba City]] and [[Los Ba\u00f1os, Laguna|Los Ba\u00f1os]], both in [[Laguna (province)|Laguna]]. The PNR uses GE locomotives such as [[PNR 900 Class|900 Class]], [[PNR 2500 Class|2500 Class]], and 5000 Class hauling Commex passenger cars as well as newly procured 18 (3 car trains, 6 sets) [[Hyundai Rotem]] DMUs and KiHa 52 for this service. [[203 series]] EMUs are now also used for Metro Commuter runs. ''MSC '' service using the new DMUs, KiHa 52, KiHa 350 and [[203 series]] EMUs is currently offered between [[Tutuban railway station|Tutuban]] and [[Alabang railway station|Alabang]] in [[Muntinlupa|Muntinlupa City]].  Currently, MSC makes 42 return services, 21 in each direction.<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.pnr.gov.ph/northbound-southbound-timetable |title = Time Table}}</ref>\n\n====Shuttle Service====\nThe ''Shuttle Service'' is a [[commuter rail]] service initially introduced on January 27, 2014. This service used Hyundai Rotem DMUs and JR KiHa 52.  There were 2 routes of the Shuttle Service, where trains stop at all stations along the routes: [[Tutuban railway station|Tutuban]] \u2013 [[Sucat railway station|Sucat]] and [[Santa Mesa railway station|Santa Mesa]] \u2013 [[Sucat railway station|Sucat]]. This train service ended May 23, 2014 to conduct maintenance on the rolling stocks and due to the consecutive three weeks of delays and cancellations of this train service.\n\nFormerly, plans for a third route plying [[Alabang railway station|Alabang]] \u2013 [[Calamba railway station|Calamba]] was to be introduced sometime in 2017. This service would use the reliveried two-car KiHa 350; This did not push through in 2018. However, with the commissioning of the new DOST Hybrid Train in 2019, this route is now under test run, currently free of charge, but with limited schedules.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.facebook.com/dost.stii/photos/a.185148651499074/3180589605288282/ |title = Aanmelden of registreren om te bekijken}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, a new shuttle line was introduced with the [[10th Avenue railway station|10th Avenue]] - [[Dela Rosa railway station|Dela Rosa]] route beginning August 1, as part of the renovation of the line and the return of train services to Caloocan City. The revived train service had its first extension towards [[Caloocan railway station|Sangandaan]], the original Caloocan station since September 10, extending through [[FTI railway station|FTI]].<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.facebook.com/pnrofficialpage/photos/a.247872075258165/2080678781977476/ |title = Philippine National Railways}}</ref> The latest so far is the northwards extension to [[Governor Pascual railway station|Governor Pascual]] (formerly called Acacia) in Malabon City since December 3, 2018.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.facebook.com/DOTrPH/photos/a.132771066862038/1252750888197378/ |title = Department of Transportation - Philippines}}</ref>\n\nA new shuttle line leading to the once-abandoned [[Carmona railway station|Carmona]] branch line is planned for reopening in 2019, and will originate from the Dela Rosa station in Makati City.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.facebook.com/DOTrPH/posts/1186365421502592 | title=Department of Transportation - Philippines}}</ref>\n\n===Bicol Commuter===\nThe ''Bicol Commuter'' service is a [[commuter rail]] service in the Bicol Region, between stations in [[Tagkawayan, Quezon]], and [[Legazpi, Albay]], with [[Naga, Camarines Sur|Naga City]] in [[Camarines Sur]] acting as a central terminal.  The service was launched on September 16, 2009, in time for the feast of [[Our Lady of Pe\u00f1afrancia]] in Naga City.<ref name=\"bicol-commuter\">{{cite news |url=http://newsinfo.inquirer.net/inquirerheadlines/nation/view/20090918-225735/Bicol-train-chugs-to-a-halt-in-test-run |title=Bicol train chugs to a halt in test run |first1=Juan |last1=Escandor Jr. |first2=Pons |last2=Caudilla |date=September 18, 2009 |newspaper=Philippine Daily Inquirer |location=Manila |accessdate=April 29, 2010 |quote=The spirit was willing, but the diesel-fed old engines were not. |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090922192110/http://newsinfo.inquirer.net/inquirerheadlines/nation/view/20090918-225735/Bicol-train-chugs-to-a-halt-in-test-run |archivedate=September 22, 2009  }}</ref> The trains made seven trips a day, alternating between Tagkawayan, [[Sipocot, Camarines Sur|Sipocot]], Naga City and Legazpi.  All services used [[KiHa 52]] in revised blue livery.\n\nAfter further reductions, only the service between Naga and Sipocot was operating as of December 2013.<ref name=\"auto1\"/>  Service resumed between Naga and Legazpi in October 2015 with one train a day.<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\nDefinitive plans to restore the entire route from Sipocot, Naga and Legazpi were bared with an inspection trip from Tutuban on September 20 with a rerailment crew, including certain areas of Quezon Province, in preparation of the restoration of more routes previously suspended.<ref name=\"auto2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/DOTrPH/posts/1466148663524265|title=Department of Transportation - Philippines|website=www.facebook.com}}</ref>\n\n==Defunct services==\n===Intercity services===\nPNR's intercity operations on its two main lines in Luzon have been indefinitely suspended since 2014. \n\nThe South Main Line then served as the primary intercity service after the permanent closure of the northern line in 1991. However, PNR also ended its regular intercity services in 2006 due to natural disasters and poor track conditions, although the ''Bicol Express'' ran irregularly between 2009 and 2014. In Camarines Sur, liquefaction of the track's embankment caused a section of the line in [[Sipocot]] to sink. This allowed the inaugural service of the new ''Bicol Express'' in 2011 to slow down to a near-stop while passing through the area.<ref>{{cite web|title=PNR Inaugural Bicol Express Train passing through the eroded embankment at Sipocot|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=hC_Htq7qjHs|website=[[Youtube]]|date=July 2, 2011|accessdate=March 1, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThere are plans to revitalize both lines. The North Main Line is currently reserved for building the fully-elevated portion of the [[North\u2013South Commuter Railway]] to [[Capas, Tarlac]]. The South Main Line is [[#South Main Line reconstruction|planned to be rebuilt and extended]] to [[Matnog, Sorsogon]]. The spur line to [[Batangas City]] will also be rebuilt. Test runs along the South Main Line were conducted in September 2019. On September 21, 2019, a KiHa 59 and a rerailment train consisting of a newly-repainted [[PNR 900 class]] locomotive and a CMC coach conducted a test run from Tutuban to Naga.<ref>{{cite web|title=PNR 917 passing Gumaca, Quezon|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=_CVnadWcsWo|website=[[Youtube]]|date=July 2, 2011|accessdate=March 1, 2020}}</ref>\n\n====North Main Line services====\nThe North Main Line was first opened when the Manila\u2013Dagupan Railway was opened in 1892. At its height between the 1950s and 1960s, the line once boasted full [[double-track railway]]s from Tutuban to Dagupan and also served until [[San Fernando, La Union]]. It also had branch lines to various areas in Central Luzon. However, its services severely deteriorated in the 1980s. All regular operations outside Metro Manila ended in 1988.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Manila North Line|url=http://asia.stationspast.net/philippines/manilla-north-line/|website=When There Were Stations: Asia|accessdate=March 8, 2020}}</ref> However, there was irregular service to [[Meycauayan railway station]] until all stations in Central Luzon were closed by the [[1991 eruption of Mount Pinatubo]].<ref>{{Cite web|title=Meycauayan|url=http://asia.stationspast.net/philippines/manilla-north-line/meycauayan/|website=When There Were Stations: Asia|accessdate=March 8, 2020}}</ref>\n\n=====''Amianan Express''=====\nThe '''''Amianan Express''''' was a night train service that opened in 1974. It left Manila by 11 PM and arrived in San Fernando by 4:30 AM the next day. It was serviced by then-new [[PNR 900 class]] diesel-electric locomotives and five coaches capable of seating 912 people. After ending in San Fernando station, commuters would take the bus to Ilocos Norte and Sur, and Benguet. Later, it was expanded into two services, the ''Amianan Day Express'' and the ''Amianan Night Express''. The ''Amianan Night Express'' ran faster than its day counterpart, the ''Amianan Day Express'', making the {{convert|260|km|mi|abbr=on}} run to [[San Fernando, La Union]] in five hours.<ref>{{cite web|title=1974 0215 PNR Amianan Expre.ss Trains|url=https://www.flickr.com/photos/fairlane/5542113081|website=[[Flickr]]|date=March 20, 2011|accessdate=March 8, 2020}}</ref>\n\n=====Baguio train-road service=====\n[[File:Stanley-1912-Mountain Wagon.jpg|thumb|1912 Stanley Motor Carriage Model 88 Mountain Wagon similar to the Benguet Auto Line vehicles traveling [[Kennon Road]] in the early 20th century.]]\nThe difficulty of terrain to build new train lines prevented both MRR and PNR to have direct train services to [[Baguio]] City. Instead, they had two luxury train services then will be accompanied by either bus or car to Baguio, and an ordinary train-bus service. During the Commonwealth era, then-MRR operated a train-bus service to [[Baguio]]. Passengers would ride the train to either Dagupan or San Fabian in Pangasinan then take the bus to Baguio City. The first service was terminated during World War II. A second service was inaugurated by the MRR by around 1955. First-class passengers would ride the train from Tutuban to Damortis station in [[Santo Tomas, La Union]], then will ride a limousine service of [[Chevrolet Bel Air]]s to Pines Hotel in Baguio City. It costed \u20b145 (equivalent to $217 in 2020 US Dollars) for this package.<ref>{{cite web|title=1955 0916 MRR Package Tour ad|url=https://www.flickr.com/photos/goriob1/5000098279/in/pool-1395212@N21/|website=[[Flickr]]|date=September 16, 2010|accessdate=March 11, 2020}}</ref> Another service was opened during the PNR era with a bus service leading to Baguio City, with buses provided by [[Hino Motors]]. This service operated until all provincial services on the North Main Line were suspended by 1988.<ref>{{cite web|title=1984 PNR MOTOR SERVICES|url=https://www.flickr.com/photos/intervene/4817155739/in/pool-1395212@N21/|website=[[Flickr]]|date=June 22, 1984|accessdate=March 11, 2020}}</ref>\n\n=====''Dagupan Express''=====\nThe '''''Dagupan Express''''' opened on February 10, 1979. It was serviced by CMC-300 class [[diesel multiple units]]. Like the ''Amianan Express'', the ''Dagupan Express'' also ended in the 1980s after all North Main Line services terminated in Tarlac.<ref>{{cite web|title=1974 0215 PNR Amianan Express Trains|url=https://www.flickr.com/photos/goriob3/6689305725|website=[[Flickr]]|date=January 12, 2012|accessdate=March 8, 2020}}</ref>\n\n=====''Ilocos Express''=====\nThe '''''Ilocos Express''''' was inaugurated on March 15, 1930. The services includes a dining car with catering provided by the [[Manila Hotel]]. Another variant of the service was the ''Baguio-Ilocos Express''. Following the modernization program of the Manila Railway Company in 1955, the Ilocos Express featured a 7A class \"De Luxe\" coach until 1979, when the lack of operable air-conditioned coaches caused a switch to a \"Tourist\"-class coach. The company also operated the ''Paniqui Express'' in the 1930s, but that was eclipsed by the ''Ilocos Express''. There were two accidents involving the service, one in 1939 and another in 1959.<ref>{{cite web|title=Official Week in Review: April 12\u2013April 18, 1959|url=http://www.officialgazette.gov.ph/1959/04/20/official-week-in-review-april-12-april-18-1959/|publisher=[[Official Gazette (Philippines)]]|accessdate=March 11, 2020}}</ref>\n\n=====''Ilocos Special''=====\nThe fastest train operated by the PNR on the North Main Line was the '''''Ilocos Special''''' (Train 26). The service started in 1973. This [[diesel multiple-unit]] (DMU) train took four hours to run the 195 kilometer portion between Manila and [[Dagupan City]].\n\n====South Main Line services====\nIntercity services on the South Main Line ran between Manila and Legazpi between 1916 and 2014, including the intermittent ''Bicol Express'' and ''Mayon/Isarog Limited'' services between 2009 and 2014. The services also briefly extended to Sorsogon in the 1960s due to the trains' popularity as a form of transportation with the masses.<ref>{{cite web|title=MRR at Lucena from ''The Philippine Herald'' dated September 7, 1961|url=https://www.flickr.com/photos/fairlane/3286676395/in/pool-1395212@N21/|website=[[Flickr]]|date=September 7, 1961|accessdate=March 11, 2020}}</ref> \n\n=====''Bicol Express''=====\n{{for|the dish named after this service|Bicol Express}}\n[[File:Philippine National Railways Route Map.jpg|thumb|upright=1.25|Route map of Bicol Express]]\n'''''Bicol Express''''' started operations between Manila and Aloneros station in [[Guinayangan]], [[Quezon]] by 1919 along with the ''Lucena Express''. A separate train between Pamplona and Tabaco, and between Port Ragay and Legazpi was opened by 1933. The Tabaco branch line during this era was closed in 1937 and instead, they linked these three sections into a single line. This formed the backbone of the South Main Line and was subsequently opened in 1938. This service was short lived and ended during the Japanese occupation of the Philippines in 1942. During this era, the Japanese government focused on rebuilding the North Main Line instead and extended it to [[Sudipen]] on the border between [[Ilocos Sur]] and [[La Union]], and the south line's rehabilitation was cut to [[San Pablo, Laguna]].<ref>{{cite web|title=1942 0619 Affairs Concerning Railway Battalion of the Imperial Japanese Forces|url=https://www.flickr.com/photos/29421855@N07/21621048500/in/pool-1395212@N21/|website=[[Flickr]]|date=January 8, 2014|accessdate=March 11, 2020}}</ref>\n\nAfter the line's post-war rehabilitation, another service was opened. The service immediately became popular with the public and more services were introduced on August 16, 1954. There are two services of this type: the daytime ''Bicol Express'' and the ''Night Express'' which was the [[Night Train]] counterpart. The ''Bicol Express'' leaving Manila was numbered 511 and its night counterpart leaving Legazpi was numbered 513. The ''Bicol Express'' leaving Legazpi was numbered 512 and the ''Night Express'' leaving Manila was numbered 514. The trains only stopped at six stations between Tutuban and Legazpi: [[Paco railway station|Paco]], [[Lucena railway station|Lucena]], [[Tagkawayan railway station|Tagkawayan]], [[Sipocot railway station|Sipocot]], [[Naga railway station|Naga]] and [[Ligao railway station|Ligao]]. Journey times lasted 13 hours between the two termini.<ref>{{cite web|title=1954 0814 New MRR Train Time Schedule|date=August 14, 1954|work=Manila Chronicle|url=https://www.flickr.com/photos/79691913@N05/12694088113|via=[[Flickr]]|accessdate=March 11, 2020}}</ref> Services were expanded until the 1970s.\n\nBy 1998, ''Bicol Express'' was the only intercity service on the South Main Line. More stations were also added into the line. It was renumbered as Train T-611 for the southbound (MA-NG) and Train T-612 for the northbound (NG-MA). Another ''Bicol Express'' train was serviced by the second version of the General Manager's train, a trainset based on modified CMC-300 series DMUs already operating in PNR service. This was numbered T-577.<ref name=\"t577\"/>\n\nSince then, the service was discontinued by 2006 after natural disasters did serious damage to the tracks and bridges. Efforts to revive the service were unsuccessful. Since 2014, operations to the [[Bicol Region]] have been suspended.<ref name=Suspended>{{cite web|title=Trains & Schedules|url=http://www.pnr.gov.ph/schedules.htm|work=Official Website|publisher=Philippine National Railways|accessdate=September 6, 2013|quote=Manila - Bicol trips are currently suspended. Please bear with us.|url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130820184432/http://www.pnr.gov.ph/schedules.htm|archivedate=August 20, 2013}}</ref> This is primarily because of typhoon damage to bridges. The PNR hoped to reopen the Bicol Express Service by about September 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gmanetwork.com/news/story/367959/economy/business/pnr-to-resume-bicol-express-in-sept|title=PNR to resume Bicol Express in Sept.|publisher=GMA News Online|date=May 9, 2014|accessdate=July 29, 2014}}</ref>  Due to the damages brought by the [[Typhoon Rammasun (2014)|Typhoon Rammasun]] (locally named Glenda), PNR announced that the Bicol Express' resumption of services would be further delayed until October and November 2014. Since then resumption of service has been repeatedly announced and then cancelled, most recently in late 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.mb.com.ph/2016/11/19/bicol-express-operations-cancelled/|title=Bicol Express operations cancelled|publisher=Manila Bulletin|date=November 19, 2016|accessdate=January 4, 2017}}</ref> This was mostly because of the remoteness of the areas and the necessity of more extensive railway repairs, which has rendered the railways towards Tutuban and back impassable until very recently.<ref name=\"auto2\"/>\n\nIt has been decided in 2019 that the ''Bicol Express'' on its present infrastructure will be discontinued permanently and a new service to Bicol will be announced after [[#South Main Line reconstruction|the new standard gauge line]] has been completed by 2021. This line will be built with Chinese funding and the trains will be served by diesel multiple units from [[CRRC Zhuzhou Locomotive]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/DOTrPH/photos/a.132771066862038/1555459547926509/|title=Department of Transportation - Philippines|website=Facebook.com}}</ref><ref name=\"crrc\" />\n\n=====''Lucena Express''=====\nThe Lucena Express was first opened in 1916 with a service between Malvar, Batangas and Aloneros in Guinayangan, Quezon. Later, the service was opened between Manila and Lucena. This train stopped at Blumentritt (San Lazaro), Santa Mesa, Paco, San Pedro, Bi\u00f1an, Santa Rosa, Calamba, Los Ba\u00f1os, College, Masaya, San Pablo, Tiaong, Taguan, Candelaria, Lutucan and Sariaya stations. It was discontinued in 1942 during the Japanese occupation and was later integrated with the ''Bicol Express'' after the war.\n\n=====''Mayon Limited''=====\nIn March 2012, another train service, the resurrected '''Mayon Limited''', ran between Tutuban and Ligao. The train ran as Mayon DeLuxe on Monday, Wednesday and Friday from Tutuban as train T-713 with three air-conditioned carriages with reclining seats. The train returned on Tuesday, Thursday and Sunday as train T-714 from Ligao. On Tuesdays, Thursdays and Sundays the train ran as Ordinary train (T-815) with non-reclining seats and cooling by fan. The departure as train T-816 was every Monday, Wednesday and Friday. The train did not run on Saturdays.<ref>{{cite news |title= Mayon Limited resumes Bicol run |url= http://www.pnr.gov.ph/pr_2012-02.htm |newspaper= Philippine National Railways Press Release |location= Manila |accessdate= March 19, 2012 |url-status= dead |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20120324194356/http://www.pnr.gov.ph/pr_2012-02.htm |archivedate= March 24, 2012 |df= mdy-all }}</ref> The trains meet at Gumaca.<ref>{{cite news |title= Mayon Limited |url= http://www.pnr.gov.ph/mayon_limited.htm |accessdate= March 19, 2012 |url-status= dead |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20120317135606/http://www.pnr.gov.ph/mayon_limited.htm |archivedate= March 17, 2012 |df= mdy-all }}</ref>  As of September 2013, all operations to the [[Bicol Region]], including the Mayon Limited, have been suspended.<ref name=Suspended />\n\nThe original '''Mayon Limited''' service decades ago was hauled alternatively by French [[Alstom]] [[locomotive]]s Series 1500 (which had engineer operator cabs at both ends and therefore did not require being turned around at neither wyes nor turntables at the end of their trips), and General Electric locomotives, especially the U12C Series 1000, UM12C Series 2000, and U14/15C Series 900{{Citation needed|date=February 2011}} and ran northward from [[Legazpi railway station|Legazpi]] up the steep gradient leading to [[Camalig railway station|Camalig]] in the foothills of the [[Mayon|Mayon Volcano]] with another locomotive pushing from the rear. The service was assigned as (Train T-577) and was considered then as the fastest and the most modern train of the Philippine National Railways operating on the South Main Line.\n\n=====''Manila Limited''=====\nThe ''Manila Limited'' was a train service between [[Tutuban station (PNR)|Manila]] and [[Iriga railway station|Iriga]]. One train leaves from these two termini each. Train 517 left Manila by 3 pm and arrive in Iriga by 4:15 am. Train 518 will leave Iriga by 2:50 pm and arrive in Manila by 2:35 am. It ended in 2006 when all regular intercity services were terminated.<ref>{{cite web|title=1991 0108 Train Schedules|url=https://www.flickr.com/photos/fairlane/5542113081|website=[[Flickr]]|date=December 17, 2012|accessdate=March 11, 2020}}</ref>\n\n=====''Prestige Express''=====\nThe '''''Prestige Express''''', also nicknamed the ''VIP Train'' from some rail enthusiasts of the time, was a [[limited express]] service from 1974 to 1981. It ran the full length of the South Main Line, but only stopped at only five stations in-between. In Manila, it only stopped at the historic [[Paco station]]. Afterwards, it stops at [[Lucena railway station|Lucena]] in [[Quezon]], [[Naga railway station|Naga]] in [[Camarines Sur]], and in [[Daraga railway station|Daraga]] and [[Ligao railway station|Ligao]] in [[Albay]]. Like all services on the South Main Line, there were added. It service was replaced by the shorter ''Pe\u00f1afrancia Express'' in 1981 that ended at Naga.<ref name=\"Nikko\">{{Cite web|title=PNR Nikko Express|url=https://05592134.at.webry.info/201703/article_8.html|website=Express Travel Blog|accessdate=March 15, 2020|lang=Japanese}}</ref>\n\nIt used two classes of Japanese-built diesel multiple units namely, the [[cowl unit]]-type multiple unit (later numbered IC-888) and the streamlined \"General Manager's Train\" or \"Nikk\u014d\" train set.<ref>{{Cite web|title=PNR VIP Train|url=https://vignette.wikia.nocookie.net/philippinetrains/images/7/72/PNR_VIP_Train.jpg/revision/latest?cb=20120804090733&path-prefix=tl|website=Philippine Trains Wikia|accessdate=March 15, 2020}}</ref> The latter train sets were named after the [[Nikk\u014d (train)|service of the same name]] and its body design was inspired by the [[157 series]] while the nose's design was inspired by the [[0 Series Shinkansen]] EMUs. Both DMUs were acquired in 1974 with the opening of the service.<ref name=\"Nikko\"/> PNR later refurbished the IC-888 trainset in order to serve the ''Bicol Express'' in 1998 until 2004.<ref name=\"t577\"/> This train was still stored in the Caloocan rail yard without any plans for scrapping as late as 2011.<ref>{{Cite web|title=PNR IC-888|url=https://www.flickr.com/photos/36157525@N02/3339543047|website=Flickr|accessdate=March 15, 2020}}</ref>\n\n=====''Pe\u00f1afrancia Express''=====\nThe PNR inaugurated the '''''Pe\u00f1afrancia Express''''' between Manila and Naga City in 1981. It became PNR's premium intercity service and also had airline-style features such as pre-recorded background music, snacks, caterers, and stewardesses. Unlike the preceding ''Prestige Express'', it did not have specialized rolling stock. It was primarily a choice between the acquired refurbished ''Nikko'' train acquired from the previous ''Prestige'' service, and later the [[PNR 900 class|900 class]] locomotive and hauled ICF baggage cars and sleeper coaches built in Madras (now [[Chennai]]), India.<ref name=\"Nikko\"/> \n\nInitially they were non-stop between Paco Station in Manila and Naga City, save for when the Pe\u00f1afrancia Express trains headed in opposite directions had to cross each other along the route in Quezon province. Later on, additional stops were added, mostly in the Bicol province of Camarines Sur with the train stopping in towns like Ragay, Sipocot, and Libmanan. This service ended by the late 1990s.<ref>{{Cite web|title=1974 0409 PNR Integrated Transport System ad|url=https://flickr.com/photos/goriob3/6634143783/|website=Flickr|accessdate=March 15, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Non-passenger services===\nThe PNR used to offer freight services, using General Electric U15C 900-series locomotives bought by the company in 1974. It is currently planned for a revival leading to the Manila North Harbor.<ref name=\"Facebook-DOTrPH\" />\n\nThere was also a limited mobile hospital service. The PNR also operated the PNR Motor Services, a bus service that led to towns that were not serviced by trains. The bus service ended by 1988.\n\n==Stations==\n[[File:Philippine National Railways.png|thumb|Entire line map of PNR. Includes defunct lines.]]\nThe Philippine National Railways operates two different rail lines, namely the North Main Line (recently revived) and the South Main Line. Formerly, there were three spur lines, which served various parts of [[Luzon]] with its [[List of Philippine National Railways stations|138 (once) active stations]].\n\n===Station layout===\nAll PNR stations were and are presently [[at-grade intersection|at-grade]], with most stations using a [[side platform]] layout. Most have only basic amenities, platforms and ticket booths. Rehabilitated stations along the Metro Manila line have been fitted with ramps for passengers using wheelchairs. Several stations have extended platforms, having an upper platform catering to DMU services, and a lower platform for regular locomotive-hauled services.\n\nAs of August 2017, most of the stations are being extended and equipped with platform-length roofing, better ticketing office, and restrooms.\n\nFuture railway systems under the PNR, such as that of the new [[North\u2013South Commuter Railway]] line, proposes elevated stations and platforms similar to the Manila LRT and MRT lines in select sections.\n\n==Modernization and Expansion Plans==\n[[File:SRTS Full Map Oct-2010 MC.svg|thumb|alt=Color-coded lines on an outline map illustrating relative positions of existing and planned routes as described in the text|The expanded network of [[rail transport in the Philippines]] before 2016.]]\n\nThe PNR system has suffered from decades of neglect and therefore, several plans to restore and expand the network has been proposed by various administrations. The [[South Korea|Republic of Korea]], the [[China|People's Republic of China]], [[Japan]] and [[Indonesia]] have contributed to these plans. Most of these concern the revitalization and modernization projects of the mainlines in Luzon.<ref name=\"southrail\">{{cite news |url=http://www.manilastandardtoday.com/?page=felMaragay_dec15_2005  |title=Rehab of busy railway |date=December 15, 2005 | first = Fel V. | last = Maragay | newspaper = [[Manila Standard Today]] |accessdate=May 2, 2010 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20060721084004/http://www.manilastandardtoday.com/?page=felMaragay_dec15_2005 |archivedate = July 21, 2006}}</ref> As of 2019, the Duterte administration plans a complete overhaul of the PNR system, which involves [[railway electrification system|electrification]] and conversion from [[3 ft 6 in gauge railways|narrow gauge]] to [[standard-gauge railway|standard gauge]], as well as from single to [[double-track railway|double track]].\n\n===Urban rail systems===\n====North\u2013South Commuter Railway====\n{{Main|North\u2013South Commuter Railway}}\nThe '''North\u2013South Commuter Railway''' (NSCR), or the '''Clark-Calamba Railway''', is the latest project to revitalize both the historic North and South Main Lines. First proposed as \"NorthRail\", a [[rapid transit]] system to connect Metro Manila to [[Clark International Airport]] that was to be co-funded by [[Spain]], it had been subject to various cancellations related to funding.<ref name=\"ABSCBN-NorthRail\" /><ref name=\"Inquirer-NorthRail\">{{cite web|url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1074035/what-went-before-the-northrail-project|title=WHAT WENT BEFORE: The Northrail Project|last=Inquirer|first=Philippine Daily|website=newsinfo.inquirer.net|language=en|access-date=February 16, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"FTCom-NorthRail\">{{cite web|url=https://www.ft.com/content/7f7f314c-522b-3a68-b6ad-4188ff607f4d|title=Philippines: China-funded Northrail project derailed|website=Financial Times|language=en-GB|access-date=February 17, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"PCIJOrg-NorthRail\">{{cite web|url=http://pcij.org/blog/2005/09/29/up-study-finds-north-rail-contract-illegal-diadvantageous-to-government|title=U.P. study finds North Rail contract illegal, disadvantageous to government|date=September 9, 2005|publisher=The PCIJ Blog|accessdate=July 29, 2014}}</ref> It finally came into shape in November 2017 after a resolution of a five-year dispute between the government and a Chinese contractor.<ref name=\"ABSCBN-NorthRail\" /> The system now includes an expansion of the line to [[Laguna (province)|Laguna]].\n\nThe NSCR will be a 36 station, {{Convert|147|km|mi|abbr=on}} elevated railway system from [[New Clark City]] in [[Capas, Tarlac]] to [[Calamba, Laguna]]. It will be the first electrified main line in the country.<ref name=\"JicaPDFmainpoints\">{{Cite report|url=http://www.jica.go.jp/topics/news/2014/ku57pq00001nkatn-att/20140917_01_0.pdf|title=Main Points of the Roadmap|date=September 2014|publisher=[[Japan International Cooperation Agency]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141011182852/http://www.jica.go.jp/topics/news/2014/ku57pq00001nkatn-att/20140917_01_0.pdf|format=PDF|url-status=dead|archivedate=October 11, 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"PSPHILGEPSGovPH\">{{Cite web|url=http://main.ps-philgeps.gov.ph/home/images/BAC/ForeignAssitedProjects/06132018/PACKAGE%20CP01/GBB%203/Pre-Bid%20Conference%20Presentation.pdf|title=PRE-BID CONFERENCE FOR CONTRACT PACKAGES CP01 and CP02 North-South Commuter Railway|date=June 1, 2018|website=philgeps.gov.ph|access-date=November 1, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180920170805/http://main.ps-philgeps.gov.ph/home/images/BAC/ForeignAssitedProjects/06132018/PACKAGE%20CP01/GBB%203/Pre-Bid%20Conference%20Presentation.pdf|archive-date=September 20, 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref> Construction on the Tutuban-Malolos segment or PNR North 1 commenced on February 15, 2019.<ref name=\"MB-TutubanMalolos\">{{Cite web|url=https://news.mb.com.ph/2019/02/16/construction-of-tutuban-malolos-railway-begins|title=Construction of Tutuban-Malolos railway begins|website=Manila Bulletin News|language=en-US|access-date=February 18, 2019}}</ref> Once fully completed by 2025, it will accommodate at least 300,000 passengers between Northern Metro Manila and Bulacan alone. While the elevated line will be served by electrified trains, the existing lines below will be used for freight trains and/or existing commuter trains.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://business.inquirer.net/265137/dotr-plans-to-integrate-new-railway-lines|title=DOTr plans to integrate new railway lines|last=Camus|first=Miguel R.|website=business.inquirer.net|language=en|access-date=February 16, 2019}}</ref>\n\n====Rapid transit involvement====\n{{main|Manila Metro Rail Transit System Line 8}}\nAs part of the infrastructure program by president [[Rodrigo Duterte]], East-West Rail was proposed by the East-West Rail Transit Corp., a consortium between Megawide, A. Brown Company Inc., and Private Equity Investment and Development Corp. It involves the financing, design, construction, and maintenance of a mostly-elevated [[rapid transit]] line from [[Quezon City|Diliman]] in Quezon City to [[Quiapo, Manila|Quiapo]] in Manila.<ref>[https://ppp.gov.ph/?ppp_projects=east-west-rail-project PNR East-West Railway Project Details] ''Public Private Partnership Center''. Retrieved January 18, 2018.</ref> In 2018, the PNR has said that it will help in building and operating the line. The line will have 11 stations on {{Convert|9.4|km|mi|sp=us}} of mostly elevated track. The project is currently awaiting approval from NEDA to proceed. It is also currently tackling right-of-way issues, such as that of the Espa\u00f1a Boulevard alignment.<ref>[https://www.rappler.com/business/182519-megawide-construction-proposed-east-west-railway-cost Megawide's proposed East-West Railway to cost $1 billion] ''[[Rappler]]''. Retrieved January 18, 2018.</ref>\n\n===Intercity projects===\n====South Main Line reconstruction====\nOn October 23, 2019, the Department of Transportation (DoTr) has announced that PNR and the Chinese government has agreed to restore and modernize the South Main Line between Calamba and [[Legazpi, Albay]] and eventually to [[Matnog, Sorsogon]]. Its gauge will also be widened from narrow gauge to standard gauge with new diesel multiple units from Chinese manufacturer [[CRRC Zhuzhou Locomotive]]. The line will initially operate as single-track before eventually upgrading to double track in the long run.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/DOTrPH/photos/a.132771066862038/1555459547926509/|title=Department of Transportation - Philippines|website=Facebook.com}}</ref><ref name=\"crrc\" />\n\nFor the meantime, PNR is currently testing a new Manila-Naga service using the newly-refurbished [[KiHa 59 series|KiHa 59]] trainset before the new South Main Line commences operations in 2021.<ref name=\"TopGear-PNR\">{{cite web|url=https://www.topgear.com.ph/news/motoring-news/pnr-manila-bicol-inspection-trip-a4354-20190924|title=PNR|last=Garcia|first=Leandre|website=TopGear Philippines|language=en|access-date=February 16, 2019}}</ref>\n\n====Calamba\u2013Batangas City railway restoration====\nThe [[Calamba, Laguna|Calamba]]\u2013[[Batangas City]] branch of the South Main Line will also be restored. The National Economic and Development Authority approved the projects in September 2017 but no clear timeline of construction has been set. In a similar fashion to the South Main Line between Manila and the Bicol Region, it will be initially be opened as a single-track standard gauge line with upgrades to double-track.<ref name=\"NEDA2017railprojects\">{{cite news|last=Dela Paz|first=Chrisee|title=NEDA Board approves Metro Manila Subway|url=https://www.rappler.com/business/181950-neda-board-approval-metro-manila-subway-pnr-railways|agency=Rappler|date=September 13, 2017|accessdate=September 14, 2017}}</ref>\n\n====Mindanao Railway====\nPresident [[Rodrigo Duterte]] expressed his support for the establishment of a railway system in the entire island of [[Mindanao]] which could be in operation after his term ends. The railway system to be built in Mindanao will have about 2,000 kilometers of track, and considered one of Rodrigo Duterte's primary infrastructure projects. The first phase, which is {{Convert|105|km|mi|sp=us}}, would start construction in the third quarter of 2018 and was expected to be completed by 2022.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://build.gov.ph/SFTFiles/Documents/BBB%20Presentation%20for%20ICEP%202017_May%203%202017.pdf|title=Build Build Build Presentation|last=|first=|date=May 20, 2017|website=Build Build Build|access-date=July 14, 2017}}</ref>\n\n====High-speed rail====\nIt was initially rumored before the announcement of the North\u2013South Commuter Railway that a \"high-speed train line\" will connect [[Metro Manila]] and [[Clark International Airport]].<ref name=\"op.gov.ph\">{{cite web |url=http://www.op.gov.ph/index2.php?option=com_content&do_pdf=1&id=24912 |title=OP.gov.ph |publisher=OP.gov.ph |date=May 9, 2013 |accessdate=August 24, 2013 }}{{Dead link|date=February 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> However, when the new line was announced, the actual maximum speed is only between {{Convert|120|km/h|mph|sp=us}} for the commuter trains and {{Convert|160|km/h|mph|sp=us}} for airport express trains and therefore does not qualify for true high-speed rail. Another speculation in form of a map for possible high-speed rail services around the country was spread throughout social media. Department of Transportation Undersecretary Timothy Batan falsified the claims but said that there are plans to build an HSR line and the current rail infrastructure being built are linked for future HSR development.<ref>{{cite news|title=Fact Check: No, this is not a map of the Philippines' high-speed rail system|url=https://www.philstar.com/headlines/2018/10/20/1861680/fact-check-no-not-map-philippines-high-speed-rail-system|agency=Agency France-Presse, through The Philippine Star|date=October 20, 2018|accessdate=November 23, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Freight revival===\nIn 2016, PNR has been interested in reviving its freight services with a planned signing of a memorandum of agreement between the railway and rail freight operator MRAIL (a [[Meralco]] subsidiary firm) for the rehabilitation of the rail lines to North Harbor and to restart the freight services starting 2017, which will also help reduce traffic congestion and truck use in the NCR.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.radyolaverdad.com/pnr-gagamitin-sa-pagde-deliver-ng-mga-kargamento-mabigat-na-trapiko-at-port-congestion-maaaring-mabawasan/|title=PNR gagamitin sa pagde-deliver ng mga kargamento; mabigat na trapiko at port congestion maaaring mabawasan|date=January 28, 2016}}</ref> If completed, MRail will jointly operate the freight service with the PNR, which will end a long absence of railway freight services in the country. This will be the second time the PNR will partner with ICTSI.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.autoindustriya.com/auto-industry-news/report-cargo-trains-to-be-revived-to-reduce-truck-traffic.html|title=Report: Cargo trains to be revived to reduce truck traffic - Auto News|date=August 8, 2016|website=AutoIndustriya.com}}</ref>\n\nA statement made by MRail Inc., a subsidiary of Metro Pacific Investments Corp., said that discussions regarding PNR freight service revival from Port of Manila to the Laguna Gateway Inland Container Terminal resulted in the appointment of a new board at the Philippine National Railways.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://business.inquirer.net/233513/mvp-group-ictsi-push-p10-b-railway-plan|title=MVP group, ICTSI to push P10-B railway plan|last=Camus|first=Miguel R.|access-date=July 20, 2017|language=en}}</ref> Representatives of PNR and ICTSI conducted an inspection of the ROW where the former railtracks leading to the North Harbor existed, signalling the start of the action to realize the cargo rail revival.<ref name=\"Facebook-DOTrPH\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/DOTrPH/posts/1215191695286631|title=Department of Transportation - Philippines|website=Facebook.com}}</ref>\n\nAs of 2019, the freight revival plans are not in effect.\n\n==Rolling stock==\nPNR has operated several types of locomotives, carriages and multiple units as part of its fleet. As of 2019, the rolling stock used are primarily powered by diesel. The [[DOST Hybrid Electric Train]] may also function as a [[battery electric multiple unit]] although it is started by a diesel engine. All present rolling stock are in {{Track gauge|1067 mm|lk=on}}. PNR also has rail mounted cranes as supporting equipment with varying capacities from 0.5 to 30 metric tons.\n\nIn late 2019, all trains in service except the 203 series-derived coaches underwent refurbishment and livery changes. The multiple units were given an orange and white color scheme and its windows were changed from having steel grills to polycarbonate windows that can resist stoning from illegal settlers while the locomotives have been painted orange.<ref name=\"rf\">[https://railf.jp/news/2019/12/10/170000.html railfan.jp] (in Japanese)</ref>\n\n===Locomotives===\nDuring the first years of its operation as the Manila-Dagupan Railway, it operated [[tank locomotive|tank engines]] mostly built in [[Scotland]]. The first tender engines appeared in 1907, when the company purchased eight [[4-6-0]] D class locomotives from the Scottish-English builder [[Kerr, Stuart and Company]]. After the [[Insular Government of the Philippine Islands|Insular Government]] took over the company by 1917, the company became the Manila Railroad Company and a number of its previous tank engines were converted to tender locomotives as well. By 1919, the American manufacturer H.K. Porter built 20 more D class locomotives. The Porter locomotives will eventually replace the old Scottish locomotives by 1927.<ref name=\"iron\">{{cite book |last=Corpuz |first=Arturo |author-link= |date= |title=The Colonial Iron Horse: Railroads and Regional Development in the Philippines, 1875-1935 |url=https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/12372360-the-colonial-iron-horse |location= |publisher=University of the Philippines Press |page= |isbn=}}</ref> Afterwards, larger steam locomotives were purchased in 1929 and then by 1944. The last steam locomotive in service with the American-owned Manila Railroad Company was the Japanese-built 300 class, based on the [[JNR Class D51]]. All steam locomotives were considered obsolete by 1956 after the dieselization of MRR began. This is despite some seeing service as late as 1963 and a number of Porter locomotives were later used in movies as late as 1989. Two British-built are preserved in Manila and Dagupan as of 2020, and others were left rotting in rail yards.<ref name=\"is\" />\n\nBy 1956, MRR ordered 20 [[GE UM12C]] and 10 streamlined diesel locomotives intended to replace the pre-war Porter D class and US Army locomotives built during World War II.<ref name=\"12c\" /> These were replaced by a large order of [[GE Universal Series]] locomotives in the 1960s and the 1970s and 10 of 75 units are still in service as of 2019, with 6 more units under refurbishment.<ref name=\"is\" /> By 2020, the PNR will receive three CC300 series diesel-hydraulic locomotives, its first order since 1973 and first reception since the last 900 class entered regular service in 1991.<ref name=\"Inquirer-7Trains\" /> On the company's website, it was initially colored black and white bearing the PNR's seal on the side of the cab. One of the locomotives bearing this livery undergone tests in January 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|title= Wujud Lokomotif pesanan dari PNR kemungkinan seperti ini IF : CC300 01|lang=Indonesian|url=https://www.picuki.com/media/2219812590079842626|website=www.picuki.com|accessdate=March 16, 2020}}</ref> The class was later recolored to orange.<ref>{{Cite web|title=CC300 series for Philippine National Railway|url=https://scontent.fmnl4-6.fna.fbcdn.net/v/t1.0-9/89082032_1506651232826419_5369264631070064640_n.jpg|website=Facebook|accessdate=March 16, 2020}}</ref> In addition, the PNR recieved four sets of switchers for depot work in Tutuban, two from INKA and another two from Italian manufactuer SVI.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+\nLocomotives\n!Class  \n!Image\n!Manufacturer\n!Year Built\n!Units Built\n!Type\n!Max Speed\n!Status\n|-\n|[[0-4-0]] \n|\n|[[Hunslet Engine Company]]\n|1885\n|2\n|[[Steam locomotive|Steam]] [[tank engine]]\n|\n|Decommissioned<ref>{{Cite web|title=Inside of the train shed at the main Manila RR Station - 1899|url=https://www.flickr.com/photos/ssave/22495090093/|website=Flickr|accessdate=March 15, 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[2-6-2]]T (1913)\n|\n|[[Kitson and Company#Kitson-Meyer|Kitson-Meyer]]\n|1913\n|4\n|Steam tank\n|\n|Decommissioned<ref name=\"lej\">{{cite journ