m tank engine (tenders were added in later service)\n|\n|Decommissioned in 1927<ref>{{Cite web|title=Hunslet Manila|url=https://vignette.wikia.nocookie.net/philippinetrains/images/d/d3/Hunslet_Manila.jpg/revision/latest?cb=20150320015121|website=Philippine Trains Wikia|accessdate=March 15, 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n|100 ([[4-8-2]])\n|\n|[[Vulcan Iron Works#Wilkes-Barre, Pennsylvania|Vulcan Iron Works]]\n|1948\n|7\n|Steam\n|{{Convert|85|km/h|mph|abbr=on}}\n|Decommissioned<ref>{{Cite web|title=1948 0331 Mountain Type Locomotive. From the ''Manila Bulletin'' - March 31, 1948 |url=https://www.flickr.com/photos/79691913@N05/12694094113/|website=Flickr|accessdate=March 16, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title=Vulcan 106|url=https://vignette.wikia.nocookie.net/philippinetrains/images/a/a8/Vulcan_106.png/revision/latest?cb=20171116143034&path-prefix=tl|accessdate=March 16, 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n|140 ([[4-6-2]])\n|\n|[[Baldwin Locomotive Works]]\n|1926-29\n|10\n|Steam\n|{{Convert|85|km/h|mph|abbr=on}}\n|Decommissioned<ref>{{Cite web|title=1940 10 MRR train. From ''The Commerce'' October 1940|url=https://www.flickr.com/photos/79691913@N05/28824654265/|website=Flickr|accessdate=March 16, 2020}}</ref><ref>Baldwin Locomotive Works List.</ref>\n|-\n|200 ([[2-10-2]])\n|\n|[[American Locomotive Company]]\n|1922\n|10\n|Steam\n|{{Convert|85|km/h|mph|abbr=on}}\n|Decommissioned<ref>{{Cite web|title=Manila RR 'Santa Fe' Locomotive 2-10-2 - 1922|url=https://www.flickr.com/photos/ssave/22821041720/|website=Flickr|accessdate=March 16, 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[JNR Class D51|300]] ([[2-8-2]])\n|\n|[[Nippon Sharyo]]\n|1951\n|10\n|Steam\n|{{Convert|85|km/h|mph|abbr=on}}\n|Decommissioned<ref name=\"lej\"/>\n|-\n|800 (2-8-2)\n|\n|Vulcan Iron Works\n|1944-45\n|45\n|Steam\n|{{Convert|100|km/h|mph|abbr=on}}\n|Decommissioned by 1956.<ref>{{Cite web|title= MRR Steam Locomotive (1956)|url=https://www.flickr.com/photos/fairlane/4331253705/|website=Flickr|access-date=March 16, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"mrr\">{{Cite web|title=The Old and the New, November 24, 1956|url=https://www.flickr.com/photos/79691913@N05/32894080044/in/pool-1395212@N21|website=Flickr|access-date=March 16, 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[PNR 900 class|900]]\n|[[File:922 alone.JPG|200px]]\n|[[GE Transportation]]\n|1973-91\n|21\n|[[Diesel locomotive|Diesel-electric]]\n|{{Convert|103|km/h|mph|abbr=on}}\n|In service<ref name=\"is\" />\n|-\n|1000\n|\n|GE Transportation\n|1956\n|10\n|Diesel-electric\n|{{Convert|100|km/h|mph|abbr=on}}\n|Decommissioned<ref>[https://www.flickr.com/photos/fairlane/4331253709/in/pool-1395212@N21/ 1957 ''Bicol Express'' train].</ref>\n|-\n|1500 (1,200&nbsp;hp BBB locomotive)\n|\n|[[Alstom|Alsthom]]\n|1966-1967\n|6\n|Diesel-electric [[boxcab]]<br>(Converted from [[Electric locomotive|electric]])\n|{{Convert|90|km/h|mph|abbr=on}}\n|Decommissioned in 1987<ref>[https://www.flickr.com/photos/fairlane/3286676399/in/photostream/ MRR/PNR Alsthom Promotional Poster (1966) \u2013 Flickr].</ref><ref>[https://www.flickr.com/photos/79691913@N05/10536055134/in/pool-1395212@N21/ ''Locomotives for PNR'' From the Sunday Chronicle - Nov. 20, 1966]</ref>\n|-\n|[[GE UM12C|2000]]\n|\n|GE Transportation\n|1956\n|20\n|Diesel-electric<br>[[Road switcher]]\n|{{Convert|60|km/h|mph|abbr=on}}\n|Decommissioned in 1997<ref name=\"12c\">[http://thedieselshop.us/GE_UM12C.HTML ''GE UM12C Roster''.] The Diesel Shop.</ref><ref name=\"b\">{{cite web |url= http://www.locopage.net/ge-expt-lst.doc|title=GE Export|author=Phil's Loco Page|date=July 4, 2015}}</ref><ref>[https://www.flickr.com/photos/fairlane/5542113579/ PNR UM12C Image (1961) \u2013 Flickr].</ref><ref name=\"mrr\"/>\n|-\n|[[PNR 2500 class|2500]]\n|[[File:PNR Kiha 52 (ex-JR) train (Anonas Street, Santa Mesa, Manila)(2017-07-12) 2.jpg|200px]]\n|GE Transportation\n|1965-79\n|43\n|Diesel-electric switcher\n|{{Convert|103|km/h|mph|abbr=on}}\n|2 units in service<ref name=\"is\" /><ref name=\"12c\" />\n|-\n|3000 (50-ton)\n|\n|GE Transportation\n|1955\n|10\n|Diesel [[switcher]]\n|{{Convert|51|km/h|mph|abbr=on}}\n|Decommissioned\n|-\n|3000 (U6B)\n|\n|GE Transportation\n|1960\n|10\n|Diesel-electric\n|{{Convert|103|km/h|mph|abbr=on}}\n|Rebuilt and renumbered as \"5000 Class\" in 1992<ref name=\"12c\" />\n|-\n|5000\n|\n|GE Transportation\n|1992 (rebuilt from 3000 Class)\n|10\n|Diesel-electric\n|{{Convert|103|km/h|mph|abbr=on}}\n|Not in active service since 2017<ref name=\"is\">[http://www.internationalsteam.co.uk/trains/philippines01.htm ''Today's Railways and Preserved Steam in the Philippines'']. International Steam. Retrieved December 18, 2019.</ref><ref name=\"12c\" /><ref>[https://www.flickr.com/photos/46273205@N02/5432493069/in/pool-1395212@N21/ DEL 5009 in 2010]</ref><ref>[https://www.flickr.com/photos/46273205@N02/26592807702/in/pool-1395212@N21/ DEL 5001 in 2016]</ref>\n|-\n|[[GE 44-ton switcher|8500]]\n|\n|GE Transportation\n|1944\n|2\n|Diesel-electric\n|\n|Decommissioned<ref>{{Cite web|title=8591 Caloocan|url=https://vignette.wikia.nocookie.net/philippinetrains/images/0/0a/8591_caloocan.png/revision/latest?cb=20170323005354&path-prefix=tl|website=Philippine Trains Wikia|access-date=March 16, 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[GE U20C|CC203]]\n|\n|[[Industri Kereta Api|PT INKA<br>GE Lokindo]]\n|1998\n|1\n|Diesel-electric\n|{{Convert|120|km/h|mph|abbr=on}}\n|Operated with ICTSI<br>Decommissioned, exported to Australia<ref name=\"12c\" />\n|-\n|CC300 ([[:id:Lokomotif CC300|id]])\n|\n|[[Industri Kereta Api|PT INKA]]\n|2020\n|3\n|[[Diesel locomotive|Diesel-hydraulic]]\n|{{Convert|120|km/h|mph|abbr=on}}\n|Undergoing tests<ref name=\"Inquirer-7Trains\">{{Cite web|url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/995374/pnr-buys-seven-more-trains-worth-p2-37-b-from-indonesia|title=PNR buys seven more trains worth P2.37-B from Indonesia|first=Dexter|last=Cabalza|website=newsinfo.inquirer.net}}</ref>\n|-\n|}\n\n===Coaches===\nPNR trains were traditionally consisted of locomotive-hauled coaches with some being refurbished from commuter rail to intercity use to accommodate the ''Bicol Express''. However, since the early 2010s, the government has put several diesel multiple units into service which were either second-hand Japanese trainsets or the Hyundai Rotem EMU that was new at the time. Currently, the only locomotive-hauled railcar type in service are the [[203 series]]-derived coaches which were EMUs stripped of motive power components which they have used during their Japanese service. By 2020, it is expected that a batch of 15 coaches will arrive from Indonesia.<ref name=\"Inquirer-7Trains\" />\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|+ Coaches\n! Class  \n! Image\n! Manufacturer\n! Year Built\n! Units Built\n! Status\n|-\n| 7A-100\n|\n| [[Nippon Sharyo]], [[Kinki Sharyo]], [[Teikoku Sharyo]], Mecano\n| 1949-1978\n| \u2014\n| Decommissioned before 1999.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.flickr.com/photos/fairlane/4831029248/|title=1973 Mayon Express Ltd|date=July 26, 2010|via=Flickr}}</ref>\n|-\n| CMC 200\n|\n| \n| 1974\n| \u2014\n| 1 unit for its rerailment crew active as of 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=_CVnadWcsWo|title=PNR 917 passing Gumaca, Quezon|date=September 21, 2019|via=Youtube}}</ref>\n|-\n| 7A-2000<br><small>([[:ja:\u56fd\u924412\u7cfb\u5ba2\u8eca|12 series passenger coach]], ex-[[Japanese National Railways]])</small>\n| [[File:PNR Tayuman 2009 MC.jpg|200px]]\n| Niigata Engineering<br>[[Subaru Corporation#History|Fuji Heavy Industries]]<br>[[Nippon Sharyo]]\n| 1969-1978<br>(acquired 1999, 2001)\n| 26\n| Decommissioned\n|-\n| 7A-2000<br><small>([[:ja:\u56fd\u924414\u7cfb\u5ba2\u8eca|14 series passenger coach]], ex-[[Japanese National Railways]])</small>\n| \n| Niigata Engineering<br>[[Subaru Corporation#History|Fuji Heavy Industries]]\n| 1972, 1974<br>(acquired 1999)\n| 5\n| Decommissioned\n|-\n| NR-00<br><small>(12 series [[:ja:\u56fd\u924412\u7cfb\u5ba2\u8eca|ja]])</small>\n| [[File:Old PNR Train.JPG|200px]]\n| Niigata Engineering<br>[[Subaru Corporation#History|Fuji Heavy Industries]]<br>[[Nippon Sharyo]]\n| 1969-1978<br>(acquired 2002)\n| 10\n| Decommissioned\n|-\n| 14 series sleeper\n| [[File:PNR Bicol Express 14-series coaches at Tutuban Yard.jpg|200px]]\n| Kawasaki Heavy Industries<br>Fuji Heavy Industries<br>''Others''\n| 1966-1979 (acquired 2011)\n| 10\n| On storage<ref name=\"sankei\">{{cite web|url=http://sankei.jp.msn.com/life/news/111126/trd11112612010008-n1.htm|date=November 26, 2011|work=Sankei News|publisher=The Sankei Shimbun & Sankei Digital|location=Japan|language=Japanese|script-title=ja:\u65e5\u672c\u306e\u4e2d\u53e4\u96fb\u8eca\u306b\u71b1\u8996\u7dda\u3000\uff19\u6708\u306b\u5f15\u9000\u3057\u305f\u901a\u52e4\u8eca\u4e21\u3001\u30d5\u30a3\u30ea\u30d4\u30f3\u3067\u7b2c\u4e8c\u306e\u4eba\u751f|trans-title=Commuter trains retired in September to live a second life in the Philippines|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120414125037/http://sankei.jp.msn.com/life/news/111126/trd11112612010008-n1.htm|archivedate=April 14, 2012|url-status=dead|accessdate=April 16, 2012}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[203 series]]-derived coaches\n|[[File:01332jfVito_Cruz_railway_station_San_Antonio_Makati_Cityfvf_04.jpg|200px]]\n|[[Kawasaki Heavy Industries]]<br>[[Nippon Sharyo]]<br>\n|1982 (acquired 2011)\n|29 (5 trains)\n|In service<ref name=\"sankei\" />\n|-\n|''INKA coaches''\n|\n| PT INKA\n| 2020\n| 15\n| Under construction<ref name=\"Inquirer-7Trains\" />\n|-\n|}\n\n===Multiple units===\nThe first multiple units in service with the PNR in 1948 were locally-constructed diesel multiple units fitted with Cummins engines, the first ones bulit by Filipinos.<ref name=\"cmi\"/> In 1955, the agency ordered another 20 diesel railcars from Japan. It was later complemented and replaced by the box-shaped CMC units built in 1973. The CMC units were used on the ''Mayon Limited'' and also became the first trains on the ''Pe\u00f1afrancia Express'' service. The inter-city CMCs were replaced by new streamlined ''Pe\u00f1afrancia Express'' trains in the 1980s while it continued to serve on the [[PNR Metro Commuter Line]] until 1999 when it was replaced by Japanese push-pull 7A class coaches.\n\nSince 2009, PNR has acquired several multiple units that were either given second-hand from Japan, or brand new from other countries. This began with the purchase of then brand-new [[PNR Hyundai Rotem DMU|Hyundai Rotem DMUs]].<ref name=\"Specs\" /> This order was followed by several orders of mostly second-hand rolling stock from Japan. In 2018, PNR signed a deal with Indonesian rolling stock manufacturer [[Industri Kereta Api]] (PT INKA) for purchase of another six sets of multiple units. By entering service in 2019, these were officially named the 8000 Class.<ref name=\"Inquirer-7Trains\" /> The Department of Science and Technology also helped in building additional stock through the Hybrid Electric Train (HET). This is the first trainset to be designed by Filipino engineers and the first locally-built multiple units since the 1948 Cummins railmotors.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://techmagus.icu/dost-hybrid-electric-train-inauguration/|title=DOST's Hybrid Electric Train Inauguration|date=April 29, 2019|work=techmagus|accessdate=April 29, 2019}}</ref> It was officially turned over to PNR on June 20, 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://mirdc.dost.gov.ph/2-uncategorised/188-dost-mirdc-turns-over-the-hybrid-electric-train-het-to-the-pnr|title=DOST-MIRDC turns over the Hybrid Electric Train (HET) to the PNR|website=The Official Website of Metals Industry Research and Development Center|language=en-gb|access-date=June 26, 2019}}</ref> The government is currently negotiating with local companies for the HET's mass production.\n\nIn 2019, with the realization of the [[North\u2013South Commuter Railway]] project that has been on hold, PNR ordered thirteen Sustina Commuter electric trains from [[Japan Transport Engineering Company]] (J-TREC) and shall begin operations by 2021.<ref name=\"BWorldOnline-DoTr\" /> The project will be the first part of the system-wide modernization of PNR from narrow gauge and diesel power to standard gauge and electric power that shall happen in the long term.\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+\nMultiple Units\n!Class\n!Image\n!Type\n!Gauge\n!Manufacturer\n!Year Built\n!Top Speed\n!Units Built\n!Status\n|-\n|''Cummins Railmotor''\n|\n|DMU\n|{{Track gauge|1067 mm|lk=on}}\n|MRR\n|1948\n|\n|\n|Decommissioned<ref name=\"cmi\">[https://www.flickr.com/photos/79691913@N05/12693933305/in/pool-1395212@N21/ 1948 0331 New Rail Motor train - Flickr.]</ref>\n|-\n|''Mitsubishi railcars''\n|\n|Diesel [[railcar]]\n|{{Track gauge|1067 mm|lk=on}}\n|[[Mitsubishi Heavy Industries]]<br>Tokyo Car<br>[[Mitsui & Co.|Daichi Bussan]]\n|1955\n|{{Convert|95|km/h|mph|abbr=on}}\n|100 (5 units per train)\n|Decommissioned in 1985<ref>[https://www.flickr.com/photos/goriob1/5075188158/in/pool-1395212@N21/ 1955 1219 New MRR Diesel Cars]</ref><ref>[https://www.flickr.com/photos/goriob1/5067477155/in/pool-1395212@N21/ 1958 0908 MRR New Rail Cars.]</ref>\n|-\n|[[KiHa 52|KiHa 52-100]]\n|[[File:Philippine Railways PNR Ligao Station.jpeg|200px]]\n|[[Diesel multiple unit|DMU]]\n|{{Track gauge|1067 mm|lk=on}}\n|[[Japanese National Railways|JNR]]\n|1962&ndash;66 (acquired 2011)\n|{{Convert|80|km/h|mph|abbr=on}}\n|7 (1/3 cars per set)\n|In service\n|-\n|[[KiHa 35|KiHa 350]]\n|[[File:PNR KiHa350 White.jpg|200px]]\n|DMU\n|{{Track gauge|1067 mm|lk=on}}\n|Fuji Heavy Industries\n|1961-66 (acquired 2011)\n|{{Convert|80|km/h|mph|abbr=on}}\n|6 (2/3/4 cars per set)\n|In service\n|-\n|[[KiHa 59 series|KiHa 59]]\n|[[File:WTNaga STAR B47a.jpg|200px]]\n|DMU\n|{{Track gauge|1067 mm|lk=on}}\n|JNR\n|1967-68<br>1989 (as KiHa 59)<br>(acquired 2011)\n|{{Convert|80|km/h|mph|abbr=on}}\n|3 (3 cars per set)\n|In service<ref name=\"Inquirer-7Trains\" />\n|-\n|''Mayon Limited'' DMU\n|\n|DMU\n|{{Track gauge|1067 mm|lk=on}}\n|JNR\n|1973\n|{{Convert|95|km/h|mph|abbr=on}}\n|16 (8 cars per set)\n|Decommissioned<ref>[https://www.flickr.com/photos/fairlane/4831029248/in/pool-1395212@N21/ 1973 Mayon Express Limited - Flickr.]</ref>\n|-\n|''Mayon Limited'' DMU\n|\n|DMU\n|{{Track gauge|1067 mm|lk=on}}\n|JNR\n|1973\n|{{Convert|95|km/h|mph|abbr=on}}\n|16 (8 cars per set)\n|Decommissioned<ref>[https://www.flickr.com/photos/fairlane/4831029248/in/pool-1395212@N21/ 1973 Mayon Express Limited - Flickr.]</ref>\n|-\n|CMC 300\n|\n|DMU\n|{{Track gauge|1067 mm|lk=on}}\n|JNR\n|1974-76\n|{{Convert|95|km/h|mph|abbr=on}}\n|60\n|Decommissioned in 1999<ref>[https://www.flickr.com/photos/25653307@N03/4224735414/in/pool-1395212@N21/ Philippine National Railways (PNR) Diesel Rail Car set lead by CMC 376 and CMC 374 trailing just south of Buendia Railway Station, Manila, Philippines.]</ref>\n|-\n|''Nikk\u014d''\n|\n|DMU\n|{{Track gauge|1067 mm|lk=on}}\n|JNR\n|1974<br>1998 (Refurbished as IC-888)\n|{{Convert|100|km/h|mph|abbr=on}}\n|26 (2-3 per train)\n|7 units refurbished in 1998 as ''Bicol Express'' T-577.<ref name=\"t577\">[https://www.flickr.com/photos/79691913@N05/8415678709/in/pool-1395212@N21/ 1998 0623 General Manager's Train T-577 - Flickr.]</ref><br>Decommissioned in 2004.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.yumpu.com/en/document/read/37144136/philippine-national-railways-rollingstock-status-aboutphilippinesph |title=Philippine National Railways Rolling Stock Status |publisher=Philippine Railway Historical Society |access-date=March 21, 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[PNR Hyundai Rotem DMU|Hyundai Rotem DMU]]\n|[[File:DMU-06_near_FTI_Station.jpg|200px]]\n|DMU\n|{{Track gauge|1067 mm|lk=on}}\n|[[Hyundai Rotem]]\n|2009-10\n|{{Convert|80|km/h|mph|abbr=on}}\n|18 (3 cars per set)\n|In service<ref name=\"Specs\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.hyundai-rotem.co.kr/Eng/Business/Rail/Business_Record_View.asp?brid=228 |title=Railway Systems-Project Record View |website=www.hyundai-rotem.co.kr |access-date=December 25, 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[DOST Hybrid Electric Train|DOST HET]] (''3000 Class'')\n|[[File:DOST Hybrid Electric Train at the PNR Alabang Station.jpg|200px]]\n|[[Hybrid train|Hybrid]] DMU/[[Battery electric multiple unit|BEMU]]\n|{{Track gauge|1067 mm|lk=on}}\n|[[Department of Science and Technology (Philippines)|DOST\u2013MIRDC]]<br>Fil-Asia Automotive\n|2019-20\n|{{Convert|80|km/h|mph|abbr=on}}\n|5 (5 cars per set)\n|Prototype unit in service, more units in order<ref name=\"pna\">{{cite news |last1=Pa-a |first1=Saul |title=1st Filipino hybrid train runs from Calamba to Manila|url=https://www.pna.gov.ph/articles/1068084 |accessdate= December 18, 2019 |agency=Philippine News Agency |date=April 24, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"pan\">[https://www.carmudi.com.ph/journal/meet-the-first-filipino-built-train-the-hybrid-electric-train-het/ ''Meet the First Filipino-Built Train: The Hybrid Electric Train (HET)'']. Carmudi.com.ph. Retrieved December 18, 2019.</ref>\n|-\n| [[PNR 8000 class|8000]]/ [[PNR 8100 class|8100]]\n|[[File:New_PNR_Cars.jpg|200px]]\n|DMU\n|{{Track gauge|1067 mm|lk=on}}\n|PT INKA\n|2019-20\n|{{Convert|100|km/h|mph|abbr=on}}\n|4 (3/4 cars per set)\n|In service<ref name=\"Inquirer-7Trains\" />\n|-\n|''[[E233 series|E233]]-type [[North\u2013South Commuter Railway|NSCR]] EMUs''\n|\n|[[Electric multiple unit|EMU]]\n|{{Track gauge|1435 mm|lk=on}}\n|[[Japan Transport Engineering Company|J-TREC]]\n|2021\n|{{Convert|120|km/h|mph|abbr=on}}\n|104 (8 cars per set)\n|On order<ref name=\"BWorldOnline-DoTr\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.bworldonline.com/dotr-prepares-to-award-rolling-stock-contract/|title=DoTr prepares to award rolling stock contract {{!}} BusinessWorld|last=Charm|first=Neil|language=en-US|access-date=December 18, 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n|''CRRC Intercity DMUs''\n|\n|DMU\n|{{Track gauge|1435 mm|lk=on}}\n|[[CRRC Zhuzhou Locomotive]]\n|2021\n|{{Convert|160|km/h|mph|abbr=on}}<ref name=\"rap\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.rappler.com/newsbreak/fact-check/243130-pnr-bicol-express-reopened-september |title=FALSE: PNR Bicol Express 'reopened' September 2019 |website=Rappler |access-date=December 25, 2018}}</ref>\n|9 (3 cars per set)\n|On order<ref name=\"crrc\">{{Cite web|url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/business/12/18/19/chinese-firm-signs-contract-to-supply-trains-for-pnr-bicol-project|title=Chinese firm signs contract to supply trains for PNR Bicol project|access-date=December 23, 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n|}\n\n==Liveries==\nThe Manila-Dagupan Railway, the Manila Railroad Company and the Philippine National Railways sported various liveries representing various eras of the company, usually to celebrate the arrival of new rolling stock. Each of these are painted by hand.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.flickr.com/photos/46273205@N02/5796451721|title=GEDC2105|website=Flickr|access-date=March 16, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Steam locomotive era (1892-1954)===\nThere were no available colored images of Manila-Dagupan Railway and the Manila Railroad Company's rolling stock before the war so the color scheme of the carriages remains unknown. However, based on the surviving locomotives, the steam locomotives owned by the two companies sported a black-only livery like most of the notable American steam engines.<ref name=\"is\"/>\n\n===Railmotor livery (1948)===\nThe Cummins railmotors were colored black or white, and orange. The pre-war carriages salvaged and refurbished in the late 1940s also used this color scheme.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.flickr.com/photos/36157525@N02/4540997038/in/photolist-7VgNdo|title=MotorTrain-1|access-date=March 16, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===MRR/PNR livery (1955)===\n[[File:PNR Logo.png|thumbnail|upright=0.9|right|Monogram of the PNR used in the 1960s. The modern PNR seal altered its colors to blue and orange.]]\nThe MRR celebrated the arrival of its first diesel rolling stock with its colors changed to dark green and yellow, or alternately to yellow-orange and dark green. The livery was retained when the Philippine government took over and renamed it the Philippine National Railways. During the transition to PNR, the old MRR monogram with a diamond-shaped seal was painted out and the PNR circular seal and monogram was placed on the front of the cab with yellow wing-like symbols outside it. The PNR acronym is also placed on the sides as well.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.flickr.com/photos/intervene/4495939839 |title=1978 LOCO No. 901|website=Flickr|access-date=March 16, 2020}}</ref> By the 1980s, the diesel multiple units will have a yellow body and the wing-like symbols are colored dark green.\n\n===Commuter Motor Coach livery (c. 1978)===\nDuring the late 1970s, the Commuter Motor Coaches used on PNR's local train services in Metro Manila and the Bicol Region was colored white and navy blue.<ref>{{Cite web|title=1980 PNR TO CARMONA|url=https://www.flickr.com/photos/intervene/3473134160|website=Flickr|accessdate=March 16, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Metrotren livery (1990)===\nWhen President [[Corazon Aquino]] inaugurated the rebranded [[PNR Metro Commuter Line|Manila commuter service]] as \"Metrotren\" in 1990, the CMC coaches were repainted to navy blue, white and red. This was also used for the 1998 restocking of the ''Bicol Express'' with the old ''Pe\u00f1afrancia Express'' IC-888 train. This was used until the mid 2000s when both multiple unit types were changed to the navy blue livery.<ref>{{Cite web|title=06649 (228) 04-02-1990 Philippine National Railways (PNR) in the yard outside the workshops I building with a Metrotren carriage in Kaloocan City, Manila, Philippines. |url=https://www.flickr.com/photos/25653307@N03/3696525933/|access-date=March 16, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Philippines 2000 livery (1997)===\nThe [[GE Universal Series]]-based 900, 2500 and 5000 classes sported a red livery celebrating Fidel Ramos' [[Philippines 2000]] program.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.flickr.com/photos/14564368@N02/33599106536/|title=908 Tayuman|access-date=March 16, 2020.}}</ref> Although the PNR revised this livery after 2000, some retained it due to lack of maintenance funds and a 900 class survived with this livery in use until 2008. Some of the freight carriages had the Philippines 2000 name spray-painted on top the old green and yellow livery.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.flickr.com/photos/79691913@N05/8535627223|title=1999 0318 PNR Philippines 2000.}}</ref>\n\n===Navy blue livery (c. 2000, 2011)===\n[[File:921 at Sucat, Muntinlupa.png|thumbnail|left|DEL 921 and 203-series coach sporting the 2011-type navy blue livery.]]\nA navy blue livery was introduced after the expiry of the Philippines 2000 program. This followed after PNR acquired locomotive-hauled 12 and 14 series coaches from Japan. There are subtle differences with the coaches used on the ''Commuter Express'' (formerly ''Metrotren'') and the ''Bicol Express''. The ''Commuter Express'' trainsets were navy blue with orange highlights while the ''Bicol Express'' were navy blue with gold highlights. The PNR symbol on the ''Commuter Express'' was white while on the ''Bicol Express'' was gold. The locomotives' colors were also changed to navy blue and orange.\n\nThis livery was re-introduced in 2011 although it was not used on the ''Bicol Express'' trainsets.\n{{-}}\n\n===Filtrack livery (2009)===\nPNR attempted to revitalize the ''Bicol Express'' in 2009 with the support of president [[Gloria Macapagal Arroyo]]. This was supported with a change of logo and liveries. The coaches in PNR service used white and orange while the locomotives' cabs were colored white while the PNR monogram logo was sealed out. The trains also sported the \"Filtrack\" brand on the coaches and on the side of the locomotives. However, this was short lived after the ''Bicol Express'' stopped its services indefinitely. By 2015, all of the rolling stock followed the 2000s navy blue livery.\n\n===INKA livery (2019)===\n[[File:INKA-8101_near_FTI_Station.jpg|thumbnail|left|An INKA-built [[PNR 8100 class]] with the new livery]].\nThe PNR announced another logo change and changes to its livery in 2019. This is after the [[Presidency of Rodrigo Duterte|Duterte administration]] under the [[Department of Transportation (Philippines)|Department of Transportation]] announced major reforms to the PNR. The PNR's monogram is now fully incorporated on a [[Seal (emblem)|seal]]-type logo, bearing the agency's name and the year it was founded. The seal was also changed from orange and blue to golden yellow and navy blue. At the same time, the rolling stock also changed its liveries with regards to the arrival of the new rolling stock from Indonesia. The [[203 series]]-based passenger cars' liveries did not change as of 2020.\n\nThe first among the old rolling stock was the [[KiHa 35]]0 and [[KiHa 59 series]] trains. After this was the Hyundai Rotem DMUs and finally, 900 series locomotive DEL 917 changed its livery to orange, similar to the upcoming CC300s. All multiple units were fitted with new windows to resist stoning. The colors however varied from one type of rolling stock to another but the common theme was the inclusion of orange (as the highlight color), white (as the main stock color), navy blue (as the side line color) and black (as the bottom color).\n\n===CRRC diesel multiple unit livery (2021)===\nThe latest effort to the revitalization of the South Main Line, particularly the ''Bicol Express'' intercity service, was unveiled in 2019 dubbed the \"South Long Haul\" project. A scale model of the train that will be used was revealed during a contract signing ceremony between the Philippine National Railways, its superior agency the Department of Transportation, and the Chinese rolling stock manufacturer CRRC Zhuzhou Locomotive. The three-car train will also feature a red-orange livery with black stripes on its windows. This train is set to arrive by 2021.\n\n{{-}}\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Transportation|Railways|Philippines}}\n* [[Department of Transportation (Philippines)|Department of Transportation]]\n* [[List of Philippine National Railways stations]]\n* [[Panay Railways]]\n* [[Rail transport in the Philippines]]\n* [[Strong Republic Transit System]]\n\n==Notes==\n:{{Note|a}} Inter-city and freight services have been suspended since 2016. The [[North\u2013South Commuter Railway]] will be the first intercity service since the discontinuation of the ''Bicol Express'' in 2016. Construction of the line commenced in 2019. There are also plans to revitalize to freight service. See [[Philippine National Railways#Freight revival|Freight revival]] for more information.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n===Further reading===\n* Uranza, Rogelio. (2002). [https://web.archive.org/web/20091229002413/http://www.cleanairnet.org/caiasia/1412/articles-37345_tp_20_uranza.pdf ''The Role of Traffic Engineering and Management in Metro Manila'']. Workshop paper presented in the Regional Workshop: Transport Planning, Demand Management and Air Quality, February 2002, Manila, Philippines. Asian Development Bank (ADB).\n* {{Cite web\n|url=http://www-wds.worldbank.org/external/default/WDSContentServer/WDSP/IB/2001/06/27/000094946_01060804031083/Rendered/PDF/multi0page.pdf\n|author=World Bank\n|title=Project Appraisal Document for the Metro Manila Urban Transport Integration Project\n|publisher=World Bank\n|date=May 23, 2001}}\n\n* [http://www.jica.go.jp Japan International Cooperation Agency Official Page] \"Revitalization of Main Line South Project(1989)\"\n* [https://www.facebook.com/ANCalerts/videos/10154331805488791/?hc_location=ufi List of stations of East West line]\n* [http://www.gmanetwork.com/news/money/economy/629155/east-west-rail-manila-bay-flood-control-projects-up-for-icc-approval/story/?just_in East West line for icc approval]\n* [http://megawide.com.ph/wp-content/uploads/2017/07/Megawide-Confirms-Participation-in-Railway-Project.pdf Statement from Megawide company]\n* [https://ppp.gov.ph/?ppp_projects=east-west-rail-project East West line the PPP Projects]\n* [http://news.abs-cbn.com/business/07/13/17/megawide-joins-quezon-city-to-manila-railway-project Megawide Joins Quezon City to Manila railway project]\n\n==External links==\n{{