the United States (1849\u201365)]]\n[[Category:Xenophobia]]\n[[Category:White nationalist parties]]\n", "name_user": "Patrick Neylan", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Know_Nothing"}
{"title_page": "Kim Cattrall", "text_new": "{{short description|British-Canadian actress}}\n{{Use Canadian English|date=June 2016}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{Infobox person\n| image        = Kim Cattrall Meet Monica Velour 2011.jpg\n| name         = Kim Cattrall\n| caption      = Cattrall in February 2011\n| birth_name   = <!--Leave blank if no stage name, per the rules-->\n| birth_date   = {{birth date and age|1956|8|21|df=yes}}\n| birth_place  = [[Mossley Hill|Mossley Hill, Liverpool]], [[Lancashire]], England\n| residence    = [[Courtenay, British Columbia]], Canada\n| occupation   = Actress\n| years_active = 1975\u2013present\n| spouse       = {{plainlist|\n* {{marriage|Larry Davis<br />|1977|1979|end={{abbr|ann.|annulled}}}}\n* {{marriage|Andre J. Lyson<br />|1982|1989|end=divorced}}\n* {{marriage|[[Mark Levinson (audio equipment designer)|Mark Levinson]]<br />|1998|2004|end=divorced}}\n}}\n}}\n'''Kim Victoria Cattrall''' ({{IPAc-en|k|\u0259|\u02c8|t|r|\u00e6|l}}; born 21 August 1956) is a British-born Canadian actress.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.freebmd.org.uk/cgi/information.pl?cite=%2BVFnub5u1SL97iTAWLHIEw&scan=1|title=Index entry|accessdate=12 August 2009|work=FreeBMD|publisher=ONS}}</ref> She is best known for her role as [[Samantha Jones (Sex and the City)|Samantha Jones]] on [[HBO]]'s ''[[Sex and the City]]'' (1998\u20132004), for which she received five [[Primetime Emmy Award|Emmy Award]] nominations and four [[Golden Globe Award]] nominations, winning the [[60th Golden Globe Awards|2002 Golden Globe]] for [[Golden Globe Award for Best Supporting Actress \u2013 Series, Miniseries or Television Film|Best Supporting Actress]]. She reprised the role in the films ''[[Sex and the City (film)|Sex and the City]]'' (2008) and ''[[Sex and the City 2]]'' (2010).\n\nCattrall made her film debut in ''[[Rosebud (1975 film)|Rosebud]]'' (1975) and went on to appear in various television roles. She came to prominence in the 1980s with films such as ''[[Ticket to Heaven]]'' (1981), ''[[Police Academy (film)|Police Academy]]'' (1984), ''[[City Limits (1985 film)|City Limits]]'' (1985), ''[[Big Trouble in Little China]]'' (1986), ''[[Mannequin (1987 film)|Mannequin]]'' (1987), ''[[Masquerade (1988 film)|Masquerade]]'' (1988), ''[[Midnight Crossing]]'' (1988), and ''[[The Return of the Musketeers]]'' (1989). She worked on several occasions with director [[Bob Clark]], appearing in four of his films: ''[[Tribute (1980 film)|Tribute]]'' (1980), ''[[Porky's]]'' (1981), ''[[Turk 182]]'' (1985), and ''[[Baby Geniuses]]'' (1999). Her other film credits include ''[[The Bonfire of the Vanities (film)|The Bonfire of the Vanities]]'' (1990), ''[[Star Trek VI: The Undiscovered Country]]'' (1991), ''[[Split Second (1992 film)|Split Second]]'' (1992), ''[[Above Suspicion (1995 film)|Above Suspicion]]'' (1995), ''[[15 Minutes]]'' (2001), ''[[Crossroads (2002 film)|Crossroads]]'' (2002), ''[[Ice Princess]]'' (2005), ''[[My Boy Jack (film)|My Boy Jack]]'' (2007), ''[[The Ghost Writer (2010 film)|The Ghost Writer]]'' (2010), and ''[[Meet Monica Velour]]'' (2010).\n\nOn stage, Cattrall appeared in the 1986 [[Broadway (theatre)|Broadway]] production of [[Michael Frayn]]'s ''[[Wild Honey (play)|Wild Honey]]''. Her other stage credits include [[August Strindberg]]'s ''[[Miss Julie]]'' ([[McCarter Theatre Center]], 1993), [[Shakespeare]]'s ''[[Antony and Cleopatra]]'' ([[Liverpool Playhouse]], 2010), [[No\u00ebl Coward]]'s ''[[Private Lives]]'' (Broadway, 2011), and [[Tennessee Williams]]' ''[[Sweet Bird of Youth]]'' ([[The Old Vic]], 2013).\n\nFrom 2014 to 2016, Cattrall starred and served as executive producer on the [[HBO Canada]] series ''[[Sensitive Skin (Canadian TV series)|Sensitive Skin]]'', for which she received a nomination for the [[Canadian Screen Award for Best Actress in a Comedy Series]]. She currently stars on the web television series ''[[Tell Me a Story (TV series)|Tell Me a Story]]'' (2018\u2013present).\n\n==Early life==\nKim Victoria Cattrall was born on 21 August 1956 in the [[Mossley Hill]] district of [[Liverpool]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.liverpoolecho.co.uk/liverpool-entertainment/echo-entertainment/2008/06/09/sex-and-the-city-star-kim-cattrall-why-i-m-so-proud-to-be-a-scouser-100252-21044664/|title=Sex and the City star Kim Cattrall: Why I'm so proud to be a Scouser|date=9 June 2008}}</ref> the daughter of secretary Gladys Shane (n\u00e9e Baugh) and construction engineer Dennis Cattrall.<ref>England & Wales, Marriage Index, Jul\u2013Aug\u2013Sep 1953, Liverpool, [[Lancashire]], 10d, 1172.</ref> When she was three months old, her family emigrated to Canada and settled in [[Courtenay, British Columbia]]. At age 11, she returned to Liverpool when her grandmother became sick. She took acting examinations at the [[London Academy of Music and Dramatic Art]],<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.lamda.ac.uk/whats-on/news-features/happy-birthday-kim-cattrall |title=Happy Birthday Kim Cattrall! |date=23 August 2016 |publisher=[[London Academy of Music and Dramatic Art]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190218021349/https://www.lamda.ac.uk/whats-on/news-features/happy-birthday-kim-cattrall |archive-date=18 February 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> but returned to Canada after one year, and moved to [[New York City]] at the age of 16 for her first acting role.\n\n==Career==\n{{BLP sources section|date=June 2018}}\nCattrall began her career after graduating from [[Georges P. Vanier Secondary School]] in 1972, when she left Canada for [[New York City]]. There, she attended the [[American Academy of Dramatic Arts]], and upon her graduation signed a five-year film deal with director [[Otto Preminger]]. She made her film debut in Preminger's action thriller ''[[Rosebud (1975 film)|Rosebud]]'' (1975). A year later, [[Universal Studios]] bought out that contract and Cattrall became one of the last participants in the contract player system of Universal (also referenced as MCA/Universal during this period) before the system ended in 1980. The Universal system's representative in New York, Eleanor Kilgallen (sister of [[Dorothy Kilgallen]]), cast Cattrall in numerous television guest-star roles. One of the first jobs Kilgallen got her was in a 1977 episode of ''[[Quincy, M.E.]]'' starring [[Jack Klugman]], whom Kilgallen also represented.\n\nIn 1978, Cattrall played the love interest of a murderous psychologist in an episode of ''[[Columbo]]'' and also in \"Blindfold\", an episode of the 1970s action series ''[[Starsky & Hutch]]'', in which Starsky (played by [[Paul Michael Glaser]]) is grief-stricken since he accidentally blinded Cattrall's character, young artist Emily Harrison, by a shot of his gun. She starred in ''[[The Bastard (1978 film)|The Bastard]]'' (1978) and ''[[The Rebels (film)|The Rebels]]'' (1979), two television miniseries based on the [[John Jakes]] novels of the same names. In 1979, she played the role of Dr. Gabrielle White on ''[[The Incredible Hulk (1978 TV series)|The Incredible Hulk]]'' and would go down in television ''Hulk'' lore as one of the few characters who knew David Banner (alter ego of the title character) was alive and was the creature. Her work in television paid off and she quickly made the transition to cinema. She starred opposite [[Jack Lemmon]] in his [[Academy Awards|Oscar]]-nominated film ''[[Tribute (1980 film)|Tribute]]'' (1980), and in ''Crossbar'', the film about a high jumper who loses his leg and still participates in the Olympic trials, with Cattrall's help. The following year, she appeared in ''[[Ticket to Heaven]]''.\n\nIn 1982, Cattrall played [[Physical education|P.E.]] teacher Miss Honeywell in ''[[Porky's]]'', followed two years later by a role in the original ''[[Police Academy (film)|Police Academy]]''. In 1985, she starred in three films: ''[[Turk 182]]'', ''[[City Limits (1985 film)|City Limits]]'' and ''[[Hold-Up (1985 film)|Hold-Up]]'', the last with French star [[Jean-Paul Belmondo]]. In 1986, she played [[Kurt Russell]]'s brainy flame in the action film ''[[Big Trouble in Little China]]''. In 1987, her lead role in the cult comedy film ''[[Mannequin (1987 film)|Mannequin]]'' proved a huge success with audiences. One of her best-known film roles is that of Lieutenant Valeris in ''[[Star Trek VI: The Undiscovered Country]]''; Cattrall assisted in developing the character by designing her own hairstyle and even helped come up with the name. Near the end of filming, Cattrall had a photographer shoot a roll of film on the ''Enterprise'' bridge set, in which she wore nothing but her [[Vulcan (Star Trek)|Vulcan]] ears. After finding out about the unauthorized photo session, [[Leonard Nimoy]] had the film destroyed.<ref>{{cite magazine |magazine=[[Femme Fatales (magazine)|Femme Fatales]] |volume= 1 |issue= 1 |date=Summer 1992 |title=Hollywood's Most Voluptuous Vulcan |first=Mark A. |last=Altman |authorlink=Mark A. Altman |page=41}}</ref>\n\nAside from her film work, Cattrall is also a stage actress, with performances in [[Arthur Miller]]'s ''[[A View from the Bridge]]'' and [[Anton Chekhov]]'s ''[[Three Sisters (play)|Three Sisters]]'' and ''[[Wild Honey (play)|Wild Honey]]'' to her credit. In addition, she can be heard reading the poetry of [[Rupert Brooke]] on the CD ''Red Rose Music SACD Sampler Volume One''. In 1997, she was cast in ''[[Sex and the City]]'', [[Darren Star]]'s series which was broadcast on HBO. As [[Samantha Jones (Sex and the City)|Samantha Jones]], Cattrall gained international recognition. She capitalized on her success by appearing in steamy television commercials promoting [[Pepsi One]]. ''Sex and the City'' ran for six seasons and ended as a weekly series in spring 2004 with 10.6 million viewers. Cattrall reprised the role of Samantha Jones in the ''[[Sex and the City (film)|Sex and the City]]'' film, released on 30 May 2008. She also appeared in [[Sex and the City 2|the sequel]] released in May 2010. For her role on the television series, she was nominated for five [[Emmy Award]]s,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.emmys.com/celebrities/kim-cattrall|title=Kim Cattrall|work=Television Academy}}</ref> and four [[Golden Globe Award]]s, winning one in 2002. She also won two ensemble [[Screen Actors Guild Award]]s, shared with her co-stars [[Sarah Jessica Parker]], [[Kristin Davis]] and [[Cynthia Nixon]]. She was ranked number eight in ''[[TV Guide]]''{{'}}s 50 sexiest stars of all-time list in 2005.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.geocities.ws/Hollywood/4616/tvg0928.html |work=geocities.ws |title=TV Guide: 50 sexiest stars of all-time |accessdate=14 June 2014}}</ref> \n\n[[File:Kim Cattrall.jpg|thumb|279x279px|Cattrall in 2007]]\nIn 2005, she appeared in the [[Walt Disney Pictures|Disney]] film ''[[Ice Princess]]'', in which she played Tina Harwood, ice skating coach of the film's lead character. She portrayed Claire, a paralysed woman who wants to die, in the [[West End theatre|West End]] drama revival of ''[[Whose Life Is It Anyway? (Play)|Whose Life Is It Anyway?]]''. In October 2006, she appeared in a West End production of [[David Mamet]]'s ''[[The Cryptogram]]'' at the [[Donmar Warehouse]] in London. Since late 2005, she has appeared in a number of British television commercials for [[Tetley|Tetley Tea]].<ref>Bowers, Simon [http://business.guardian.co.uk/story/0,,1579024,00.html \"The decline of the British cuppa\"], ''The Guardian'', 27 September 2005.</ref> In July 2006, a commercial for [[Nissan]] cars, which featured Cattrall as Samantha Jones, was withdrawn from [[New Zealand]] television, apparently because of complaints about its innuendo.<ref>{{cite news|work=NineMSN |url=http://news.ninemsn.com.au/article.aspx?id=115922 |title=Kim Cattrall ad too saucy for Kiwis |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071013145538/http://news.ninemsn.com.au/article.aspx?id=115922 |archivedate=13 October 2007 |date=21 July 2006}}</ref> She later starred alongside [[Brendan Gleeson]] in [[John Boorman]]'s film ''[[The Tiger's Tail]]'' (2006), a [[black comedy]] that focuses on the impact of the [[Celtic Tiger]] economy on Irish people. On [[ITV (TV network)|ITV]], she starred alongside [[David Haig]], [[Daniel Radcliffe]] and [[Carey Mulligan]] in ''[[My Boy Jack (film)|My Boy Jack]]'', the story of author [[Rudyard Kipling]]'s search for his son lost in the [[World War I|First World War]].\n\nIn early 2009, Cattrall played Amelia Bly in [[Roman Polanski]]'s well received ''[[The Ghost Writer (film)|The Ghost Writer]]'', which was released in 2010. On 16 June 2009, it was announced that Cattrall would receive a star on [[Canada's Walk of Fame]] in [[Toronto]], Ontario. The induction ceremony was held on 12 September 2009.<ref name=\"ind2009\">{{cite web|url=http://www.canadaswalkoffame.com/news/the-stars-align-12th-annual-canadas-walk-fame |title=The Stars Align at the 12th Annual Canada's Walk of Fame |date=16 June 2009 |publisher=Canada's Walk of Fame |accessdate=16 June 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090620081814/http://www.canadaswalkoffame.com/news/the-stars-align-12th-annual-canadas-walk-fame |archivedate=20 June 2009}}</ref> In November 2009, while filming ''[[Sex and the City 2]]'' in [[Marrakech]], Morocco, she took part in a seminar, 'Being directed' with director [[John Boorman]] as part of the third edition of the [[Arts in Marrakech Festival]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.aimbiennale.org |title=AiM Festival/AiM Biennale, Riad El Fenn, Marrakech :: Home |publisher=Aimbiennale.org |accessdate=31 December 2010}}</ref> On 24 February 2010, Cattrall began a run in the West End of London at the [[Vaudeville Theatre]] as leading lady, Amanda, opposite [[Matthew Macfadyen]], in a revival of [[No\u00ebl Coward]]'s play ''[[Private Lives]]''. She performed until 3 May 2010. In the same year, Cattrall starred as Gloria Scabius (alongside Macfadyen once again) in the critically acclaimed Channel 4 adaptation of [[William Boyd (writer)|William Boyd]]'s novel ''[[Any Human Heart (miniseries)|Any Human Heart]]''.\n\nCattrall played [[Cleopatra]] in a production of ''[[Antony and Cleopatra]]'', directed by [[Janet Suzman]], opposite [[Jeffery Kissoon]] as Anthony, in [[Liverpool]] at the [[Liverpool Playhouse|Playhouse]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.everymanplayhouse.com/ |title=Everyman and Playhouse Theatre, Liverpool \u2013 Everyman and Playhouse |publisher=Everymanplayhouse.com |accessdate=31 December 2010}}</ref> in October 2010, with a subsequent revival at [[Chichester Festival Theatre]] (with [[Michael Pennington]] as Anthony) in September 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cft.org.uk/antony-and-cleopatra |title=Antony and Cleopatra &#124; Festival2012|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121005102823/http://www.cft.org.uk/antony-and-cleopatra |archivedate=5 October 2012 |work=Chichester Festival Theatre |accessdate=26 September 2012}}</ref> In 2010, Cattrall was named an Honorary Fellow of [[Liverpool John Moores University]] in recognition of her contributions to the dramatic arts.<ref>{{cite web|author=Shonagh Wilkie |url=http://www.ljmu.ac.uk/NewsUpdate/index_114645.htm |title=Kim Cattrall to receive Honorary Fellowship |publisher=Ljmu.ac.uk |accessdate=31 December 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101217190415/http://ljmu.ac.uk/NewsUpdate/index_114645.htm |archivedate=17 December 2010}}</ref> In 2011, Cattrall reprised her role as Amanda in a production of [[No\u00ebl Coward]]'s ''[[Private Lives]]'' opposite Canadian actor [[Paul Gross]] in Toronto and on Broadway.<ref>{{cite news|url= http://www.newsday.com/entertainment/theater/kim-cattrall-wrapped-up-in-private-lives-1.3359403/ |title= Kim Cattrall wrapped up in 'Private Lives'|newspaper= Newsday|date=1 December 2011|accessdate= 11 August 2012}}</ref> That year, Cattrall also appeared in ''Uptown Downstairs Abbey'', the [[Comic Relief#2011 event|Comic Relief]] parody of the critically acclaimed historical television dramas ''[[Downton Abbey]]'' and ''[[Upstairs, Downstairs (1971 TV series)|Upstairs, Downstairs]]''. Playing Lady Grantham, she starred alongside [[Jennifer Saunders]], [[Joanna Lumley#Media work|Joanna Lumley]], [[Victoria Wood]], [[Harry Enfield]], [[Patrick Barlow]], [[Dale Winton]], [[Olivia Colman]], [[Tim Vine]], [[Simon Callow]], [[Michael Gambon]] and [[Harry Hill]].\n\nFrom June to August 2013, Cattrall was scheduled to star in [[the Old Vic]]'s production of [[Tennessee Williams]]'s ''[[Sweet Bird of Youth]]'', directed by Olivier Award-winner [[Marianne Elliott (director)|Marianne Elliott]]. In 2014, she starred as Davina Jackson in [[HBO Canada]]'s ''[[Sensitive Skin (Canadian TV series)|Sensitive Skin]]''. On 17 July 2015, Cattrall was cast in the title role of ''Linda'' in a new play by [[Penelope Skinner]], to be directed by Michael Longhurst and produced at London's [[Royal Court Theatre]]. She was forced to drop out of that production a few days before the opening, due to \"chronic, debilitating insomnia\". She returned to New York and started a program of cognitive behaviour therapy to train herself to be able to sleep better. The therapy was successful; it included developing certain evening rituals, removing electronic devices from her bedroom, and limiting the use of the bed to two activities, one of which would be sleeping. Meanwhile, for the scheduled December 2015 opening of Skinner's play, actress [[Noma Dumezweni]] took over the role to much acclaim and publicity.<ref>Taylor, Paul. \"Linda, Royal Court, London, review: Takedown of the beauty industry is only skin deep.\" ''Independent''. 6 December 2015.</ref><ref>Mulkerrins, Jane. \"Kim Cattrall on insomnia: 'What I felt in spades was how alone I was'\". ''The Telegraph''. 8 June 2016.</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/entertainment-arts-33565248 |title=Kim Cattrall returns to London stage in Linda |work=[[BBC News]] |date=17 July 2015 |accessdate=18 July 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\n[[File:Kim Cattrall 1999.jpg|right|thumb|180px|Cattrall at the [[HBO]] party after the 1999 Emmy Awards]]\nCattrall has been married three times and does not have children. Her first marriage, from 1977 to 1979, was to Larry Davis, but was annulled. Her second marriage, from 1982 to 1989, was to Andre J. Lyson: the couple lived in [[Frankfurt]] , where she learned to speak [[German language|German]] fluently, but she admits she has forgotten a lot over the years.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=_NTONT7eTqw |title=Kim Cattrall speaking German at the Life Ball 2008 |website=Youtube.com |date=21 May 2010 |accessdate=25 April 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bunte.de/stars/samantha-aus-satc_did_2286.html |title=Bunte: Kim Cattrall in Interview |language=German |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110928044034/http://www.bunte.de/stars/samantha-aus-satc_did_2286.html |archivedate=28 September 2011 }} \u2013 Catrall was in Frankfurt from 1982 to 1985.</ref><ref>[http://www.gala.de/starbase2/index/profile/name/Kim+Cattrall/biografie/Kim+Cattrall Gala: Kim Cattrall] lived in Frankfurt with Andre J. Lyson in the 1980s.</ref> Her third marriage, from 1998 to 2004, was to audio designer and jazz bassist [[Mark Levinson (audio equipment designer)|Mark Levinson]]; the couple co-wrote the book ''Satisfaction: The Art of the Female Orgasm'' (2002).<ref>{{cite news|url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9901E0D6163AF934A15752C0A9649C8B63&sec=&spon=&pagewanted=all |title=SATC's Samantha & Husband Write Female Orgasm Book |newspaper=The New York Times |date=27 January 2002 |accessdate=25 April 2011 |first=Alex |last=Kuczynski}}</ref>\n\nCattrall briefly dated former Canadian Prime Minister [[Pierre Trudeau]] (and in 2016 was misidentified on ''[[60 Minutes]]'', from a 1981 photo, as the mother of his son [[Justin Trudeau|Justin]]).<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.thestar.com/news/gta/2016/03/06/60-minutes-mixes-up-margaret-trudeau-and-kim-cattrall.html |first=Vanessa |last=Lu |title=60 Minutes mixes up Margaret Trudeau and Kim Cattrall |work=[[Toronto Star]] |date=6 March 2016 |accessdate=10 August 2019 }}</ref><ref name=\"guard\">{{cite news |first=Ruth |last=Huntman |title=Kim Cattrall: 'I don't want to be in a situation for even an hour where I'm not enjoying myself' |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=10 August 2019 |url=https://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/2019/aug/10/kim-cattrall-i-dont-want-to-be-in-a-situation-for-even-an-hour-where-im-not-enjoying-myself- |accessdate=10 August 2019 }}</ref> She has also been connected to actor [[Daniel Benzali]], musician [[Gerald Casale]] of the [[New wave music|new wave]] group [[Devo]], French public intellectual [[Bernard-Henri L\u00e9vy]], and her ''[[Whose Life Is It Anyway? (Play)|Whose Life Is It Anyway?]]'' co-star, [[Alexander Siddig]].<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.contactmusic.com/new/xmlfeed.nsf/mndwebpages/cattrall%20finds%20love%20with%20costar |title=Cattrall finds love with co-star |magazine=Contactmusic.com |accessdate=25 April 2011}}</ref>\n\nShe holds British and Canadian citizenship.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.theguardian.com/culture/2011/jun/24/kim-cattrall-interview| title=Kim Cattrall: You can take the girl out of Liverpool...| work=The Guardian| date=24 June 2011| accessdate=23 May 2017}}</ref> In 2010 and 2011, Cattrall said that reports that she became a US citizen were incorrect.<ref>{{cite news|title=Q {{!}} Past Episodes Sept.&nbsp;28, 2011|url=http://www.cbc.ca/q/episodes/|accessdate=29 September 2011 | work=CBC News}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Grimshaw |first=Sophy |url=http://sophygrimshaw.com/kim-cattrall-queen-of-parts/ |title=Kim Cattrall: Queen of parts |website=sophygrimshaw.com |date=October 2010 |accessdate=7 August 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140927144857/http://sophygrimshaw.com/kim-cattrall-queen-of-parts/ |archivedate=27 September 2014  }}</ref>\n\nOn 21 December 1988, Cattrall was booked on [[Pan Am Flight 103|Pan Am 103]] from London to New York City. She missed the doomed flight because she made the last-minute decision to go shopping at [[Harrods]] to buy her mother a teapot.<ref name=\"strombo\">{{Cite web|last=Strombo|title=My defining moment: Kim Cattrall on how shopping saved her life|date=14 January 2014|website=Youtube|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=X53ytx3VSos|access-date=21 May 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.smh.com.au/lifestyle/actor-kim-cattral-is-here-to-prove-that-men-make-passes-at-girls-with-glasses-20170126-gtytdh.html|title=Actor Kim Cattrall on cheating death, embracing therapy and working at 60|last=Hooton|first=Amanda|date=26 January 2017|work=The Sydney Morning Herald|language=en|access-date=21 May 2019}}</ref> She re-booked herself on a flight that departed Heathrow 45 minutes after Pan Am 103 departed.<ref name=\"strombo\"/> When she landed in New York, she learned that her original flight was brought down by a terrorist bomb over [[Lockerbie]], Scotland, killing all 259 people on the plane and 11 people on the ground.\n\nIn August 2009, Cattrall took part in the [[BBC One]] documentary series ''[[Who Do You Think You Are? (UK TV series)|Who Do You Think You Are?]]'', in which she discovered some facts about George Baugh, her grandfather. Baugh, who disappeared in 1938, having abandoned his family \u2013 including Cattrall's then 8-year-old mother and her two younger sisters \u2013 turned out to have [[bigamy|bigamously]] married his new wife, Isabella Oliver, the following year in [[Tudhoe]], [[County Durham]], and subsequently had another four children. She was told that in 1961, he emigrated to Australia, where he became a [[postmaster]], retired in 1972, and died in [[Sydney]] in 1974.<ref>{{cite news|last=Rhys |first=Steffan |url=http://www.walesonline.co.uk/news/wales-news/sex-city-star-kim-cattralls-2087822 |title=Sex and the City star Kim Cattrall's tragic roots |work=[[Western Mail (Wales)|Western Mail]] |date=12 August 2009 |location=Cardiff |accessdate=7 August 2014}}</ref> Cattrall's mother and aunts had known nothing of their father's life after he left until they heard what the ''Who Do You Think You Are?'' researchers had discovered, nor had the family previously seen a clear photograph of him. An edited version of the episode was later shown as a part of the [[Who Do You Think You Are? (U.S. TV series)|U.S. series of the same name]].\n\nOn 4 February 2018, Cattrall tweeted that her brother, Christopher, had disappeared in [[Alberta]]. She asked for public help in finding him.<ref name=brother>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-us-canada-42937825 |title=Kim Cattrall announces brother's death after earlier plea for information |work=[[BBC News]] |date=4 February 2018}}</ref> He was found dead several hours later, having taken his own life.<ref name=brother/><ref name=\"guard\"/>\n\n==Filmography==\n===Film===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! Notes\n|-\n| 1975\n| ''[[Rosebud (1975 film)|Rosebud]]''\n| Joyce Donnovan\n|\n|-\n| 1977\n| ''[[Deadly Harvest (1977 film)|Deadly Harvest]]''\n| Susan Franklin\n|\n|-\n| 1979\n| ''[[Crossbar (film)|Crossbar]]''\n| Katie Barlow\n|\n|-\n| 1980\n| ''[[Tribute (1980 film)|Tribute]]''\n| Sally Haines\n|\n|-\n| 1981\n| ''[[Ticket to Heaven]]''\n| Ruthie\n|\n|-\n| 1982\n| ''[[Porky's]]''\n| Miss Lynn \"Lassie\" Honeywell\n|\n|-\n| 1984\n| ''[[Police Academy (film)|Police Academy]]''\n| [[List of Police Academy characters#Cadet Karen Thompson|Cadet Karen Thompson]]\n|\n|-\n| 1985\n| ''[[Turk 182]]''\n| Danny Boudreau\n|\n|-\n| 1985\n| ''[[City Limits (1985 film)|City Limits]]''\n| Wickings\n|\n|-\n| 1985\n| ''[[Hold-Up (1985 film)|Hold-Up]]''\n| Lise\n|\n|-\n| 1986\n| ''[[Big Trouble in Little China]]''\n| Gracie Law\n|\n|-\n| 1987\n| ''[[Mannequin (1987 film)|Mannequin]]''\n| Ema \"Emmy\" Hesire\n|\n